# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cancer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cancer/abl1] The ABL1 protein is a non-receptor tyrosine kinase that contains both Src homology 3 (SH3) and Src homology 2 (SH2) domains, followed by a tyrosine kinase domain.
[src:cancer/abl1] These domains are involved in regulating its activity and interactions with other proteins.
[src:cancer/abl1] ABL1 also contains signals that allow it to shuttle between the nucleus and cytoplasm, as well as regions that enable binding to the actin cytoskeleton.
[src:cancer/abl1] The *ABL1* proto-oncogene encodes a cytoplasmic and nuclear protein tyrosine kinase that has been implicated in processes of cell differentiation, cell division, cell adhesion, and stress response such as DNA repair.
[src:cancer/abl1] Activity of ABL1 protein is negatively regulated by its SH3 domain, and deletion of the SH3 domain turns ABL1 into an oncogene.
[src:cancer/abl1] The DNA-binding activity of the ubiquitously expressed ABL1 tyrosine kinase is regulated by CDC2-mediated phosphorylation, suggesting a cell cycle function for ABL1.
[src:cancer/abl1] A characteristic translocation, t(9;22), results in the head-to-tail fusion of the *BCR* and *ABL1* genes, leading to a fusion gene present in many cases of chronic myelogenous leukemia.
[src:cancer/abl1] The *ABL1* gene is expressed as either a 6- or a 7-kb mRNA transcript, with alternatively spliced first exons spliced to the common exons 2–11.
[src:cancer/abl1] This gene is a partner in a fusion gene with the *BCR* gene in the Philadelphia chromosome, a characteristic abnormality in chronic myelogenous leukemia (CML) and rarely in some other leukemia forms.
[src:cancer/abl1] In CML, the gene is activated by being translocated within the BCR (breakpoint cluster region) gene on chromosome 22.
[src:cancer/abl1] This new fusion gene, *BCR-ABL*, encodes an unregulated, cytoplasm-targeted tyrosine kinase that allows the cells to proliferate without being regulated by cytokines.
[src:cancer/abl1] This, in turn, allows the cell to become cancerous.
[src:cancer/abl1] The resulting BCR-ABL1 fusion protein exhibits constitutive tyrosine kinase activity and activates multiple downstream signaling pathways, including RAS/MAPK, PI3K/AKT, and Src family kinases, which promote uncontrolled cell proliferation and survival.
[src:cancer/abl1] This can also lead to a clonal myeloproliferative disorder.
[src:cancer/abl1] The BCR-ABL protein can be inhibited by various small molecules.
[src:cancer/abl1] One such inhibitor is imatinib mesylate, which occupies the tyrosine kinase domain and inhibits BCR-ABL's influence on the cell cycle.
[src:cancer/abl1] Second generation BCR-ABL tyrosine-kinase inhibitors are also under development to inhibit BCR-ABL mutants resistant to imatinib.
[src:cancer/abl1] There is some evidence that the expression of Abl is regulated by the microRNA miR-203.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Regular monthly vaginal bleeding during the reproductive years, menstruation, is a normal physiologic process.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The causes of abnormal vaginal bleeding vary by age, and such bleeding can be a sign of specific medical conditions ranging from hormone imbalances or anovulation to malignancy (cervical cancer, vaginal cancer or uterine cancer).
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] In young children, or elderly adults with cognitive impairment, the source of bleeding may not be obvious, and may be from the urinary tract (hematuria) or the rectum rather than the vagina, although most adult women can identify the site of bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] When vaginal bleeding occurs in prepubertal children or in postmenopausal women, it always needs medical attention.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Vaginal bleeding during pregnancy can be normal, especially in early pregnancy.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] However, bleeding may also indicate a pregnancy complication that needs to be medically addressed.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] During pregnancy bleeding is usually, but not always, related to the pregnancy itself.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The treatment of vaginal bleeding is dependent on the specific cause, which can often be determined through a thorough history, physical, and medical testing.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The parameters for normal menstruation have been defined as a result of an international process designed to simplify terminologies and definitions for abnormalities of menstrual bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The causes of abnormal vaginal bleeding vary by age.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Bleeding in children is of concern if it occurs before the expected time of menarche and in the absence of appropriate pubertal development.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Bleeding before the onset of pubertal development deserves evaluation.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] It could result from local causes or from hormonal factors.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] In children, it may be challenging to determine the source of bleeding, and "vaginal" bleeding may actually arise from the bladder or urethra, or from the rectum.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Vaginal bleeding in the first week of life after birth is a common observation, and pediatricians typically discuss this with new mothers at the time of hospital discharge.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] During childhood, one of the most common causes of vaginal bleeding is presence of a foreign body in the vagina which may be caused by normal self-exploration or can be indicative of sexual abuse.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] This is often associated with pelvic pain, foul discharge, or recurrent genitourinary infections.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Hormonal causes include central precocious puberty, or peripheral precocious puberty (McCune–Albright syndrome), or primary hypothyroidism.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Genitourinary injury is also a common cause, and is often the most common cause of hospitalization or emergency department visits for prepubertal vaginal bleeding, comprising up to 45% of such cases.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The most common genitourinary injury is the straddle injury, which often occurs during a fall, often on a sharp edge, and can cause lacerations between the labial folds.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] While vaginal bleeding in children is typically alarming to parents, most causes are benign, although sexual abuse or tumor are particularly important to exclude.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] In premenopausal women, bleeding can be from the uterus, from vulvar or vaginal lesions, or from the cervix.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] A gynecologic examination can be performed to determine the source of bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Bleeding may also occur as a result of a pregnancy complication, such as a spontaneous abortion (miscarriage), ectopic pregnancy, or abnormal growth of the placenta, even if the woman is not aware of the pregnancy.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] This possibility must be kept in mind with regard to diagnosis and management.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Generally, the causes of abnormal uterine bleeding in premenopausal women who are not pregnant include fibroids, polyps, hormonal disorders such as polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), blood clotting disorders, and cancer.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Infections such as cervicitis or pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) can also result in vaginal bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Postcoital bleeding is bleeding that occurs after sexual intercourse.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Lastly, a normal and common side effect of birth control includes vaginal spotting or bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] A more specific clinical guideline, called the PALM-COEIN system, has been developed by FIGO (International Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics) to classify the causes of abnormal uterine bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] This acronym stands for *P*olyp, *A*denomyosis, *L*eiomyoma, *M*alignancy and Hyperplasia, *C*oagulopathy, *O*vulatory Disorders, *E*ndometrial Disorders, *I*atrogenic Causes, and *N*ot Classified.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The PALM causes are related to uterine structural, anatomic, and histolopathologic causes that can be assessed with imaging techniques such as ultrasound or biopsy to view the histology of a lesion.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The COEIN causes of abnormal bleeding are not related to structural causes.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Vaginal bleeding occurs during 15–25% of first trimester pregnancies.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Of these, half go on to miscarry and half bring the fetus to term.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] There are a number of causes including complications to the placenta, such as placental abruption and placenta previa.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Other causes include miscarriage, ectopic pregnancy, molar pregnancy, incompetent cervix, uterine rupture, and preterm labor.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Bleeding in early pregnancy may be a sign of a threatened or incomplete miscarriage.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] In the second or third trimester a placenta previa (a placenta partially or completely overlying the cervix) may bleed quite severely.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Placental abruption is often associated with uterine bleeding as well as uterine pain.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Light spotting early on in pregnancy can be a result of the fertilized egg implanting into the uterus.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Additionally, during pregnancy, the blood supply to the cervix increases, which can cause the cervix to be more friable and bleed more easily than a non-pregnant woman's cervix.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Because of this, some light spotting after intercourse can be normal.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] However, bleeding may also indicate a pregnancy complication that needs to be medically addressed and any vaginal bleeding during pregnancy should prompt a call to the patient's obstetric provider.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] While many of the causes of premenopausal bleeding still apply to perimenopausal women, there is an additional cause of abnormal uterine bleeding in this category of women, which is the hormonal changes.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Around age 40, women's hormones begin to change and this can cause variation in menstrual patterns.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] This can last for years, with menstrual periods lasting various lengths and coming at various intervals.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Menopause is considered complete after a woman has gone 12 months without a menstrual period.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Endometrial atrophy, uterine fibroids, and endometrial cancer are common causes of postmenopausal vaginal bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] About 10% of cases are due to endometrial cancer.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Uterine fibroids are benign tumors made of muscle cells and other tissues located in and around the wall of the uterus.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Women with fibroids do not always have symptoms, but some experience vaginal bleeding between periods, pain during sex, and lower back pain.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The cause of the bleeding can often be discerned on the basis of the bleeding history, physical examination, and other medical tests as appropriate.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] The physical examination for evaluating vaginal bleeding typically includes visualization of the cervix with a speculum, a bimanual exam, and a rectovaginal exam.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] These are focused on finding the source of the bleeding and looking for any abnormalities that could cause bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] In addition, the abdomen is examined and palpated to ascertain if the bleeding is abdominal in origin.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Typically a pregnancy test is performed as well.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] If bleeding was excessive or prolonged, a CBC may be useful to check for anemia.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Abnormal endometrium may have to be investigated by a hysteroscopy with a biopsy or a dilation and curettage.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] In 2011, the International Federation of Gynaecology and Obstetrics (FIGO) recognized two systems designed to aid research, education, and clinical care of women with abnormal uterine bleeding (AUB) in the reproductive years.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] In postmenopausal vaginal bleeding, the primary goal of any diagnostic evaluations is to exclude endometrial hyperplasia and malignancy.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Transvaginal ultrasonography and endometrial sampling are common methods for an initial evaluation.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Guidelines from the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) recommend transvaginal ultrasonography as an appropriate first-line procedure to identify which patients are at higher risk of endometrial cancer.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Endometrial sampling can be obtained either by an endometrial biopsy using an endometrium sampling device such as a pipelle or by dilation and curettage (D&C) with or without a hysteroscopy.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Severe acute bleeding, such as caused by ectopic pregnancy and post-partum hemorrhage, leads to hypovolemia (the depletion of blood from the circulation), progressing to shock.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] This is a medical emergency and requires hospital attendance and intravenous fluids, usually followed by blood transfusion.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Once the circulating volume has been restored, investigations are performed to identify the source of bleeding and address it.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Uncontrolled life-threatening bleeding may require uterine artery embolization (occlusion of the blood vessels supplying the uterus), laparotomy (surgical opening of the abdomen), occasionally leading to hysterectomy (removal of the uterus) as a last resort.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] A possible complication from protracted vaginal blood loss is iron deficiency anemia, which can develop insidiously.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Eliminating the cause will resolve the anemia, although some women require iron supplements or blood transfusions to improve the anemia.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] While many forms of vaginal bleeding are normal and do not require treatment, other forms will require medical attention.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Hormonal management is usually the first option used to treat acute abnormal uterine bleeding.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] These hormonal medications include birth control pills, medroxyprogesterone acetate (brand name Depo-Provera), and conjugated equine estrogen.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Long-term treatments include hormonal IUD insertion, birth control pills, progestin pills or progestin shots (Depo-Provera), and NSAIDs such as ibuprofen Certain medications may not be safe for certain women.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Women with blood clotting disorders may also need to see a hematologist.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Surgical treatments may also be considered if the bleeding is severe or if there are reasons patients cannot take the hormonal medications listed above.
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] These options include dilation & curettage, endometrial ablation, and hysterectomy (removal of the uterus).
[src:cancer/abnormal-vaginal-bleeding] Hysterectomy will result in infertility, so surgical decisions will include women's preferences regarding future fertility when possible.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Lead singer and guitarist Nick Thomas (born May 25, 1984) grew up in Sioux Falls, South Dakota, and began learning how to play guitar at 11 years old.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Thomas attended Roosevelt High School in the city and sang with the school concert choir and men's choir.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] He began performing at local venues with his acoustic guitar at 15-years-old and self-released his first punk rock and acoustic CD titled *The Blur of Motions* in 2000 with Prairie Dog Studios.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Thomas envisioned the Spill Canvas in the summer of 2001 as a collage of unique musical sounds and ideas coming together to form a unique palette.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Vocalist Becca Flinn approached Thomas after a solo show and the two formed the beginnings of the band, adding bassist Alan Burkhard and violinist Hannah Peskey.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The band combined a subtle symphonic sound with aggressive acoustic rock.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Flinn, Burkhard, and Peskey dropped out of the group less than a year after joining.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Thomas retained the band name as a solo project while performing as a guitarist and backup vocalist for Nodes of Ranvier until his departure in early 2003 to pursue developing his band full time.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The Spill Canvas self-released its first five-song CD titled *Concept EP* in May 2003, produced at Cathouse Studios in Sioux Falls.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The band signed with Florida-based, independent label One Eleven Records shortly after the CD release.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Label owner Brad Fischetti discovered the band on the online streaming website MP3.com.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The band's first widespread album, *Sunsets and Car Crashes*, which was written, produced, and performed by Thomas, was released by One Eleven Records on April 20, 2004.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Thomas was joined by members Joe Beck, Brian Anderson, Ross Wheeler, and Brandon Aegerter to tour after the release of *Sunsets and Car Crashes*.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Wheeler, Anderson, and Aegerter later left the group and were replaced by Scott McGuire and Dan Ludeman.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The four members collectively wrote what would be The Spill Canvas' second album, *One Fell Swoop*.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The album was released August 9, 2005, by One Eleven Records once again.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On their official page in late 2006, the band announced a change of label through a news post by bassist Scott McGuire; "Also, did I mention that there is a new record label in the picture?
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Being a better creative fit than McGuire, Heil quickly became a permanent member of the outfit.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On May 1, 2007, the band released an EP entitled *Denial Feels So Good*, to hold their fans over until their new album arrived.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The EP consisted of three original songs and two covers.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Marc Sheaffer, a keyboardist from Sioux Falls, played keys on "Gold Dust Woman".
[src:cancer/abnormalities] After the release of the EP, the band played on the entire summer 2007 Warped Tour, promoting the upcoming release of their third album and first major label debut *No Really, I'm Fine*.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The new album was recorded in March and April 2007, and in Alternative Press Issue 229, it was confirmed that Anthony Green of Circa Survive and Andrew McMahon of Jack's Mannequin would be guests on the new album.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Green sang backup vocals on the song "Bleed, Everyone's Doing It", and McMahon played keyboards in the re-recorded version of the song "Saved", a song originally recorded for the soundtrack of the motion picture, *Superman Returns*.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On July 26, 2007, *No Really, I'm Fine* was rumored to be the title of the upcoming album.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Soon after, however, websites such as Amazon.com and Best Buy had listed the new album with the title *Conduit*.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On August 28, 2007, the band posted a Myspace bulletin saying that the album was going to be titled *No Really, I'm Fine*.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The album was released under this title on October 2, 2007.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The band went on a Fall tour across North America in the Fall of 2007, named "All Your Favorite Spots".
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The tour was supported by Meg & Dia, Playradioplay!, and Treaty of Paris.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On January 23, 2008, it was confirmed on Yellowcard's official MySpace that The Spill Canvas would be touring with them in a spring acoustic tour.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] In February 2008, they headed to Europe with Plain White T's and The Fold.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] In the summer of 2008, The Spill Canvas headlined a national tour, supported by Steel Train and Ludo.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Up-and-coming pop-punkers Sing It Loud joined them for the first half of the tour, with Liam and Me joining for the end.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] They were joined by Motion City Soundtrack for the final leg of the tour.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] In late 2008, they toured with OneRepublic, The Hush Sound, and Augustana.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On this tour, most vocalists from all of the opening bands, including Nick, came up during Augustana's set to perform Traveling Wilbury's hit "Handle With Care", trading off lead vocals.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] In early 2009, The Spill Canvas toured the UK supporting You Me at Six alongside Emarosa.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Abnormalities, featuring new music from the band, was released on January 12, 2010, through The Spill Canvas store and digital retailers.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Their next EP, Realities, was released shortly thereafter on April 13.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On July 27, 2010, their newest album, Formalities, saw digital release.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The album contains songs previously seen on both Realities and Abnormalities, along with acoustic versions of songs from those EPs and two brand new songs.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] They spent the summer of 2010 touring with the Goo Goo Dolls and Switchfoot.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On January 13, 2011, an article in the Sioux Falls Argus Leader said that the band may be on a temporary hiatus and there was no indication when, if ever, the band would return.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On May 15, 2011, after a long time of being inactive on Twitter, "Someday soon" was tweeted from The Spill Canvas.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On August 11, 2011, the band posted, "Tell your friends to follow @thespillcanvas we are going to be posting lots of interesting news and announcements in the coming weeks!" on Twitter.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The Spill Canvas played a "reunion show" in their hometown of Sioux Falls, SD on October 28, 2011, during which they announced they are no longer on a label and plan to record a new album, with a Kickstarter campaign raising funds to record it.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On January 21, 2012, The Spill Canvas posted a studio update on YouTube.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The Spill Canvas will release their new album, *Gestalt*, on May 22, 2012, according to their Facebook account.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The song "Parallels and Money" was included on this album.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] On April 20, 2012, The Spill Canvas released the first track off of their upcoming album *Gestalt*, called "To Chicago" on their PureVolume account.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The song reached number one on PureVolume.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] After a hiatus lead singer Nick Thomas released a solo record funded by Kickstarter called *Shadowars* in 2014.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The singer has been touring the record nationally with spill canvas bassist Landon Heil and new drummer Bryce Job.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Thomas and Job embarked on a brief east coast acoustic run with another South Dakota band Paradise Fears and William Beckett of The Academy Is.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Then the full Nick Thomas band toured in November with co-headliners Deleasa and Cassio Monroe spanning the east coast.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] In December the NT band headlined a tour including Midwest and West coast dates with openers My Body Sings Electric from Denver.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Afterwards, the Nick Thomas band performed on the Radio Revival Tour with Secondhand Serenade and Ryan Cabrera.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The Spill Canvas joined Motion City Soundtrack's 10 year anniversary of Commit This To Memory tour in July 2015.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The band also celebrated a 10-year anniversary tour of One Fell Swoop in August 2015.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The band started a requestour in April 2016.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] They allowed fans to vote for their favorite songs to be played at the show.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] While not officially a member of The Spill Canvas, Mike Naran played guitar as part of their live show since joining them in Cambridge, Massachusetts in August, 2015.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The band worked on a new album, which followed up their album "Gestalt".
[src:cancer/abnormalities] The Spill Canvas performed at Webster Hall on May 4, 2017, during Emo Nite LA's NYC concert.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] Evan Pharmakis (lead guitar/vocals)joined the band at the tail end of 2017, shortly before the band was on tour with Punchline and Selfish Things from Toronto, supporting their new EP Hivemind, released July 20, 2018.
[src:cancer/abnormalities] In January 2021, the band announced that they would release a new album, "Conduit", on March 5, 2021, via Pure Noise Records.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) has listed acetaldehyde as a Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxins with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In 1835, Liebig named it "aldehyde", and in the middle of the century the name was altered to "acetaldehyde".
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In 2013, global production was about 438,000 tonnes.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Before 1962, ethanol and acetylene were the major sources of acetaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Since then, ethylene is the dominant feedstock.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In the 1970s, the world capacity of the Wacker-Hoechst direct oxidation process exceeded two million tonnes annually.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Smaller quantities can be prepared by the partial oxidation of ethanol in an exothermic reaction.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This process typically is conducted over a silver catalyst at about 500–650 °C (950–1,200 °F).
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This method is one of the oldest routes for the industrial preparation of acetaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Prior to the Wacker process and the availability of cheap ethylene, acetaldehyde was produced by the hydration of acetylene.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The mechanism involves the intermediacy of vinyl alcohol, which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The reaction is conducted at 90–95 °C (194–203 °F), and the acetaldehyde formed is separated from water and mercury and cooled to 25–30 °C (77–86 °F).
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In the wet oxidation process, iron(III) sulfate is used to reoxidize the mercury back to the mercury(II) salt.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The resulting iron(II) sulfate is oxidized in a separate reactor with nitric acid.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The enzyme Acetylene hydratase discovered in the strictly anaerobic bacterium *Pelobacter acetylenicus* can catalyze an analogous reaction without involving any compounds of mercury.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] However, it has thus far not been brought to any large-scale or commercial use.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In this endothermic process, ethanol vapor is passed at 260–290 °C over a copper-based catalyst.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The process was once attractive because of the value of the hydrogen coproduct, but in modern times is not economically viable.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The hydroformylation of methanol with catalysts like cobalt, nickel, or iron salts also produces acetaldehyde, although this process is of no industrial importance.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Similarly noncompetitive, acetaldehyde arises from synthesis gas with modest selectivity.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The equilibrium constant is 6×10−7 at room temperature, thus that the relative amount of the enol form in a sample of acetaldehyde is very small.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] At room temperature, acetaldehyde (CH3CH=O) is more stable than vinyl alcohol (CH2=CHOH) by 42.7 kJ/mol: Overall the keto-enol tautomerization occurs slowly but is catalyzed by acids.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Photo-induced keto-enol tautomerization is viable under atmospheric or stratospheric conditions.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This photo-tautomerization is relevant to the Earth's atmosphere, because vinyl alcohol is thought to be a precursor to carboxylic acids in the atmosphere.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a common electrophile in organic synthesis.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In addition reactions acetaldehyde is prochiral.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] It is used primarily as a source of the "CH3C+H(OH)" synthon in aldol reactions and related condensation reactions.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Grignard reagents and organolithium compounds react with MeCHO to give hydroxyethyl derivatives.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In one of the more spectacular addition reactions, formaldehyde in the presence of calcium hydroxide adds to MeCHO to give pentaerythritol, C(CH2OH)4 and formate.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In a Strecker reaction, acetaldehyde condenses with cyanide and ammonia to give, after hydrolysis, the amino acid alanine.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can condense with amines to yield imines; for example, with cyclohexylamine to give *N*-ethylidenecyclohexylamine.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] These imines can be used to direct subsequent reactions like an aldol condensation.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] It is also a building block in the synthesis of heterocyclic compounds.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In one example, it converts, upon treatment with ammonia, to 5-ethyl-2-methylpyridine ("aldehyde-collidine").
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Three molecules of acetaldehyde condense to form "paraldehyde", a cyclic trimer containing C-O single bonds.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Similarly condensation of four molecules of acetaldehyde give the cyclic molecule metaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Paraldehyde can be produced in good yields, using a sulfuric acid catalyst.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Metaldehyde is only obtained in a few percent yield and with cooling, often using HBr rather than H2SO4 as the catalyst.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] At −40 °C (−40 °F) in the presence of acid catalysts, polyacetaldehyde is produced.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] There are two stereomers of paraldehyde and four of metaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The German chemist Valentin Hermann Weidenbusch (1821–1893) synthesized paraldehyde in 1848 by treating acetaldehyde with acid (either sulfuric or nitric acid) and cooling to 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] He found it quite remarkable that when paraldehyde was *heated* with a trace of the same acid, the reaction went the other way, recreating acetaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Although vinyl alcohol is a tautomeric form of acetaldehyde (§ Tautomerization to vinyl alcohol), polyvinyl alcohol cannot be produced from acetaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde forms a stable acetal upon reaction with ethanol under conditions that favor dehydration.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The product, CH3CH(OCH2CH3)2, is formally named 1,1-diethoxyethane but is commonly referred to as "acetal".
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This can cause confusion as "acetal" is more commonly used to describe compounds with the functional groups RCH(OR')2 or RR'C(OR'')2 rather than referring to this specific compound — in fact, 1,1-diethoxyethane is also described as the diethyl acetal of acetaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a precursor to vinylphosphonic acid, which is used to make adhesives and ion conductive membranes.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In the liver, the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase oxidizes ethanol into acetaldehyde, which is then further oxidized into harmless acetic acid by acetaldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] These two oxidation reactions are coupled with the reduction of NAD+ to NADH.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In the brain, the enzyme catalase is primarily responsible for oxidizing ethanol to acetaldehyde, and alcohol dehydrogenase plays a minor role.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The last steps of alcoholic fermentation in bacteria, plants, and yeast involve the conversion of pyruvate into acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide by the enzyme pyruvate decarboxylase, followed by the conversion of acetaldehyde into ethanol.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The latter reaction is again catalyzed by an alcohol dehydrogenase, now operating in the opposite direction.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Many East Asian people have an ALDH2 mutation which makes them significantly less efficient at oxidizing acetaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] On consuming alcohol, their bodies tend to accumulate excessive amounts of acetaldehyde, causing the so-called alcohol flush reaction.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] They develop a characteristic flush on the face and body, along with "nausea, headache and general physical discomfort".
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Ingestion of the drug disulfiram, which inhibits ALDH2, leads to a similar reaction .
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Traditionally, acetaldehyde was mainly used as a precursor to acetic acid.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This application has declined because acetic acid is produced more efficiently from methanol by the Monsanto and Cativa processes.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an important precursor to pyridine derivatives, pentaerythritol, and crotonaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Urea and acetaldehyde combine to give a useful resin.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetic anhydride reacts with acetaldehyde to give ethylidene diacetate, a precursor to vinyl acetate, which is used to produce polyvinyl acetate.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The global market for acetaldehyde is declining.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Demand has been impacted by changes in the production of plasticizer alcohols, which has shifted because *n*-butyraldehyde is less often produced from acetaldehyde, instead being generated by hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Likewise, acetic acid, once produced from acetaldehyde, is made predominantly by the lower-cost methanol carbonylation process.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The impact on demand has led to increase in prices and thus slowdown in the market.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] China is the largest consumer of acetaldehyde in the world, accounting for almost half of global consumption in 2012.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Major use has been the production of acetic acid.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Other uses such as pyridines and pentaerythritol are expected to grow faster than acetic acid, but the volumes are not large enough to offset the decline in acetic acid.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] As a consequence, overall acetaldehyde consumption in China may grow slightly at 1.6% per year through 2018.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Western Europe is the second-largest consumer of acetaldehyde worldwide, accounting for 20% of world consumption in 2012.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] As with China, the Western European acetaldehyde market is expected to increase only very slightly at 1% per year during 2012–2018.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] However, Japan could emerge as a potential consumer for acetaldehyde in the next five years due to newfound use in commercial production of butadiene.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The supply of butadiene has been volatile in Japan and the rest of Asia.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This should provide the much needed boost to the flat market, as of 2013.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The threshold limit value is 25 ppm (STEL/ceiling value) and the MAK (Maximum Workplace Concentration) is 50 ppm.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] At 50 ppm acetaldehyde, no irritation or local tissue damage in the nasal mucosa is observed.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] When taken up by the organism, acetaldehyde is metabolized rapidly in the liver to acetic acid.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Only a small proportion is exhaled unchanged.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] After intravenous injection, the half-life in the blood is approximately 90 seconds.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Many serious cases of acute intoxication have been recorded.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde naturally breaks down in the human body.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is an irritant of the skin, eyes, mucous membranes, throat, and respiratory tract.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This occurs at concentrations as low as 1000 ppm.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Symptoms of exposure to this compound include nausea, vomiting, and headache.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] These symptoms may not happen immediately.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The perception threshold for acetaldehyde in air is in the range between 0.07 and 0.25 ppm.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] At such concentrations, the fruity odor of acetaldehyde is apparent.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Conjunctival irritations have been observed after a 15-minute exposure to concentrations of 25 and 50 ppm, but transient conjunctivitis and irritation of the respiratory tract have been reported after exposure to 200 ppm acetaldehyde for 15 minutes.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In addition, acetaldehyde is damaging to DNA and causes abnormal muscle development as it binds to proteins.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde induces DNA interstrand crosslinks, a form of DNA damage.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] These can be repaired by either of two replication-coupled DNA repair pathways.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The first is referred to as the FA pathway, because it employs gene products defective in Fanconi's anemia patients.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This repair pathway results in increased mutation frequency and altered mutational spectrum.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The second repair pathway requires replication fork convergence, breakage of the acetaldehyde crosslink, translesion synthesis by a Y-family DNA polymerase and homologous recombination.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] People with a genetic deficiency for the enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde into acetic acid may have a greater risk of Alzheimer's disease.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] A study of 818 heavy drinkers found that those exposed to more acetaldehyde than normal through a genetic variant of the gene encoding for ADH1C, ADH1C*1, are at greater risk of developing cancers of the upper gastrointestinal tract and liver.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The drug disulfiram (Antabuse) inhibits acetaldehyde dehydrogenase, an enzyme that oxidizes the compound into acetic acid.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Metabolism of ethanol forms acetaldehyde before acetaldehyde dehydrogenase forms acetic acid, but with the enzyme inhibited, acetaldehyde accumulates.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] If one consumes ethanol while taking disulfiram, the hangover effect of ethanol is felt more rapidly and intensely (disulfiram-alcohol reaction).
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] As such, disulfiram is sometimes used as a deterrent for alcoholics wishing to stay sober.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is a potential contaminant in workplace, indoors, and ambient environments.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Moreover, the majority of humans spend more than 90% of their time in indoor environments, increasing any exposure and the risk to human health.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] In a study in France, the mean indoor concentration of acetaldehydes measured in 16 homes was approximately seven times higher than the outside acetaldehyde concentration.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The living room had a mean of 18.1±17.5 μg m−3 and the bedroom was 18.2±16.9 μg m−3, whereas the outdoor air had a mean concentration of 2.3±2.6 μg m−3.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] It has been concluded that volatile organic compounds (VOC) such as benzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, toluene, and xylenes have to be considered priority pollutants with respect to their health effects.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] It has been pointed that in renovated or completely new buildings, the VOCs concentration levels are often several orders of magnitude higher.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The main sources of acetaldehydes in homes include building materials, laminate, PVC flooring, varnished wood flooring, and varnished cork/pine flooring (found in the varnish, not the wood).
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] It is also found in plastics, oil-based and water-based paints, in composite wood ceilings, particle-board, plywood, treated pine wood, and laminated chipboard furniture.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The use of acetaldehyde is widespread in different industries, and it may be released into waste water or the air during production, use, transportation and storage.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Sources of acetaldehyde include fuel combustion emissions from stationary internal combustion engines and power plants that burn fossil fuels, wood, or trash, oil and gas extraction, refineries, cement kilns, lumber and wood mills and paper mills.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also present in automobile and diesel exhaust.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] As a result, acetaldehyde is "one of the most frequently found air toxics with cancer risk greater than one in a million".
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Natural tobacco polysaccharides, including cellulose, have been shown to be the primary precursors making acetaldehyde a significant constituent of tobacco smoke.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] It has been demonstrated to have a synergistic effect with nicotine in rodent studies of addiction.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde is also the most abundant carcinogen in tobacco smoke; it is dissolved into the saliva while smoking.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde has been found in cannabis smoke.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] This finding emerged through the use of new chemical techniques that demonstrated the acetaldehyde present was causing DNA damage in laboratory settings.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Many microbes produce acetaldehyde from ethanol, but they have a lower capacity to eliminate the acetaldehyde, which can lead to the accumulation of acetaldehyde in saliva, stomach acid, and intestinal contents.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Fermented food and many alcoholic beverages can also contain significant amounts of acetaldehyde.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde, derived from mucosal or microbial oxidation of ethanol, tobacco smoke, and diet, appears to act as a cumulative carcinogen in the upper digestive tract of humans.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] According to European Commission's Scientific Committee on Consumer Safety's (SCCS) "Opinion on Acetaldehyde" (2012) the cosmetic products special risk limit is 5 mg/L and acetaldehyde should not be used in mouth-washing products.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Acetaldehyde can be produced by the photo-oxidation of polyethylene terephthalate (PET), via a Type II Norrish reaction.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] Although the levels produced by this process are minute acetaldehyde has an exceedingly low taste/odor threshold of around 20–40 ppb and can cause an off-taste in bottled water.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The level at which an average consumer could detect acetaldehyde is still considerably lower than any toxicity.
[src:cancer/acetaldehyde] The yeast *Candida albicans* in patients with potentially carcinogenic oral diseases has been shown to produce acetaldehyde in quantities sufficient to cause problems.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Although some medical studies have suggested that acupressure may be effective at helping manage nausea and vomiting, insomnia, low back pain, migraines, and constipation, among other things, such studies have been found to have a high likelihood of bias.
[src:cancer/acupressure] There is no reliable evidence for the effectiveness of acupressure.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Acupressure originated in ancient China, developing as part of traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Acupressure and acupuncture are generally held to have originated in China, with the earliest references appearing in documents from a few hundred years before the Common Era.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The *Huangdi Neijing* (Yellow Emperor's Classic of Internal Medicine), dating from approximately 100 BCE, represents the first document that unequivocally described an organized system of diagnosis and treatment recognized as acupuncture.
[src:cancer/acupressure] This foundational text, compiled over 2000 years ago during China's Warring States period, established the concepts of meridians through which Qi (vital energy) flowed, though precise anatomical locations of acupuncture points developed later.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Historical evidence indicates that acupuncture has been practiced in China for more than 3000 years and subsequently spread to Europe and America from the sixteenth to nineteenth centuries.
[src:cancer/acupressure] An alternative theory posits that acupressure originated in India around 560 BCE during the Buddhist era, was taught at Nalanda and Takshshila, and later transmitted to China by a migrating Buddhist monk.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Proponents of this theory note that major points of Indian acupressure and Chinese acupuncture share similarities.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The subsequent development and promotion of this medicine in China is attributed to official support and extensive research conducted there.
[src:cancer/acupressure] A 2011 systematic review of 43 studies of acupressure's effectiveness at treating symptoms found that the nature of these 43 studies "indicated a significant likelihood of bias." Thirty-five of the 43 studies had concluded that acupressure was effective at treating certain symptoms.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The authors of this systematic review concluded that this "review of clinical trials from the past decade did not provide rigorous support for the efficacy of acupressure for symptom management.
[src:cancer/acupressure] A 2011 Cochrane review of four trials using acupuncture and nine studies using acupressure to control pain in childbirth concluded that "acupuncture or acupressure may help relieve pain during labour, but more research is needed".
[src:cancer/acupressure] An acupressure wristband that is claimed to relieve the symptoms of motion sickness and other forms of nausea provides pressure to the P6 acupuncture point, a point that has been extensively investigated.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The Cochrane Collaboration reviewed the use of P6 for nausea and vomiting, and found it to be effective for reducing post-operative nausea, but not vomiting.
[src:cancer/acupressure] EBM reviewer Bandolier said that P6 in two studies showed 52% of patients with control having a success, compared with 75% with P6.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Clinical use of acupressure frequently relies on the conceptual framework of traditional Chinese medicine.
[src:cancer/acupressure] There is no physically verifiable anatomical or histological basis for the existence of acupuncture points or meridians.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Proponents reply that TCM is a prescientific system that continues to have practical relevance.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Acupuncturists tend to perceive TCM concepts in functional rather than structural terms (e.g., as being useful in guiding evaluation and care of patients).
[src:cancer/acupressure] Trials using placebo have not demonstrated any statistically significant effect but concluded that acupressure is safe to use along with conventional treatment.
[src:cancer/acupressure] There are several different instruments for applying nonspecific pressure by rubbing, rolling, or applying pressure on the reflex zones of the body.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The acuball is a small ball made of rubber with protuberances that is heatable.
[src:cancer/acupressure] It is used to apply pressure and relieve muscle and joint pain.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The energy roller is a small cylinder with protuberances.
[src:cancer/acupressure] It is held between the hands and rolled back and forth to apply acupressure.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The foot roller (also "krupa chakra") is a round, cylindrical roller with protuberances.
[src:cancer/acupressure] It is placed on the floor, and the foot is rolled back and forth over it.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The power mat (also pyramid mat) is a mat with small pyramid-shaped bumps that you walk on.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The spine roller is a bumpy roller containing magnets that is rolled up and down the spine.
[src:cancer/acupressure] The Teishein is one of the original nine classical acupuncture needles described in the original acupuncture texts.
[src:cancer/acupressure] Even though it is described as an acupuncture needle, it did not pierce the skin.
[src:cancer/acupressure] It is used to apply rapid percussion pressure to the points being treated.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Genetic risk factors may include Down syndrome, Li–Fraumeni syndrome, or neurofibromatosis type 1.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Environmental risk factors may include significant radiation exposure or prior chemotherapy.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Evidence regarding electromagnetic fields or pesticides is unclear.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Some hypothesize that an abnormal immune response to a common infection may be a trigger.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The underlying mechanism involves multiple genetic mutations that results in rapid cell division.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The excessive immature lymphocytes in the bone marrow interfere with the production of new red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Diagnosis is typically based on blood tests and bone marrow examination.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Acute lymphoblastic leukemia is typically treated initially with chemotherapy aimed at bringing about remission.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This is then followed by further chemotherapy, typically over some years.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Treatment usually also includes intrathecal chemotherapy since systemic chemotherapy can have limited penetration into the central nervous system, and the central nervous system is a common site for relapse of acute lymphoblastic leukemia.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Treatment can also include radiation therapy if ALL has spread to the brain.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Stem cell transplantation may be used if the disease recurs following standard treatment.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Additional treatments such as Chimeric antigen receptor T cell immunotherapy are being used and further studied.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Acute lymphoblastic leukemia affected about 876,000 people globally in 2015 and resulted in about 111,000 deaths.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] It occurs most commonly in children, particularly those between the ages of two and five.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In the United States it is the most common cause of cancer and death from cancer among children.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Acute lymphoblastic leukemia is notable for being the first disseminated cancer to be cured.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Survival for children increased from under 10% in the 1960s to 90% in 2015.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Survival rates remain lower for babies (50%) and adults (35%).
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Initial symptoms can be nonspecific, particularly in children.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Over 50% of children with leukemia had one or more of five features: a liver one can feel (64%), a spleen one can feel (61%), pale complexion (54%), fever (53%), and bruising (52%).
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Additionally, recurrent infections, feeling tired, arm or leg pain, and enlarged lymph nodes can be prominent features.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The B symptoms, such as fever, night sweats, and weight loss, are often present as well.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Central nervous system (CNS) symptoms such as cranial neuropathies due to meningeal infiltration are identified in less than 10% of adults and less than 5% of children, particularly mature B-cell ALL (Burkitt leukemia) at presentation.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The cancerous cell in ALL is the lymphoblast.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Normal lymphoblasts develop into mature, infection-fighting B-cells or T-cells, also called lymphocytes.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Signals in the body control the number of lymphocytes so neither too few nor too many are made.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In ALL, the normal development of some lymphocytes and the control over the number of lymphoid cells become defective.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] ALL emerges when a single lymphoblast gains many mutations to genes that affect blood cell development and proliferation.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In childhood ALL, this process begins at conception with the inheritance of some of these genes.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These genes, in turn, increase the risk that more mutations will occur in developing lymphoid cells.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Certain genetic syndromes, like Down Syndrome, have the same effect.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Environmental risk factors are also needed to help create enough genetic mutations to cause disease.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Evidence for the role of the environment is seen in childhood ALL among twins, where only 10–15% of both genetically identical twins get ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Since they have the same genes, different environmental exposures explain why one twin gets ALL, and the other does not.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Infant ALL is a rare variant that occurs in babies under one year of age.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] *KMT2A* (formerly *MLL*) gene rearrangements are most common and happen in the embryo or fetus before birth.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These rearrangements result in increased expression of blood cell development genes by promoting gene transcription and through epigenetic changes.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In contrast to childhood ALL, environmental factors are not thought to play a significant role.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Aside from the *KMT2A* rearrangement, only one extra mutation is typically found.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Environmental exposures are not needed to help create more mutations.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Common inherited risk factors include mutations in *ARID5B*, *CDKN2A/2B*, *CEBPE*, *IKZF1*, *GATA3*, *PIP4K2A* and, more rarely, *TP53*.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These genes play important roles in cellular development, proliferation, and differentiation.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Individually, most of these mutations are low risk for ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] A significant risk of disease occurs when a person inherits several of these mutations together.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The uneven distribution of genetic risk factors may help explain differences in disease rates among ethnic groups.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] For instance, the *ARID5B* mutation is less common in ethnic African populations.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Several genetic syndromes also carry an increased risk of ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These include: Down syndrome, Fanconi anemia, Bloom syndrome, X-linked agammaglobulinemia, severe combined immunodeficiency, Shwachman–Diamond syndrome, Kostmann syndrome, neurofibromatosis type 1, ataxia-telangiectasia, paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria, and Li–Fraumeni syndrome.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Fewer than 5% of cases are associated with a known genetic syndrome.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Rare mutations in *ETV6* and *PAX5* are associated with a familial form of ALL with autosomal dominant patterns of inheritance.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The environmental exposures that contribute to the emergence of ALL are contentious and a subject of ongoing debate.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] High levels of radiation exposure from nuclear fallout are a known risk factor for developing leukemia.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Evidence whether lesser radiation, as from x-ray imaging during pregnancy, increases the risk of disease remains inconclusive.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Studies that have identified an association between x-ray imaging during pregnancy and ALL found only a slightly increased risk.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Exposure to strong electromagnetic radiation from power lines has also been associated with a slightly increased ALL risk.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This result is questioned as no causal mechanism linking electromagnetic radiation with cancer is known.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] High birth weight (greater than 4000 g or 8.8 lbs) is also associated with a small increased risk.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The mechanism connecting high birth weight to ALL is also unknown.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Evidence suggests that secondary leukemia can develop in individuals treated with certain types of chemotherapy, such as epipodophyllotoxins and cyclophosphamide.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] There is some evidence that a common infection, such as influenza, may indirectly promote the emergence of ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The delayed-infection hypothesis states that ALL results from an abnormal immune response to infection in a person with genetic risk factors.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Delayed development of the immune system due to limited disease exposure may result in excessive production of lymphocytes and increased mutation rate during an illness.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Several studies have identified lower ALL rates among children with greater exposure to illness early in life.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Very young children who attend daycare have lower rates of ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Evidence from many other studies looking at disease exposure and ALL is inconclusive.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Some researchers have linked the hygiene hypothesis.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Several characteristic genetic changes lead to the creation of a leukemic lymphoblast.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These changes include chromosomal translocations, intrachromosomal rearrangements, changes in the number of chromosomes in leukemic cells, and additional mutations in individual genes.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Chromosomal translocations involve moving a large region of DNA from one chromosome to another.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This move can result in placing a gene from one chromosome that promotes cell division to a more actively transcribed area on another chromosome.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The result is a cell that divides more often.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] An example of this includes the translocation of *C-MYC*, a gene that encodes a transcription factor that leads to increased cell division, next to the immunoglobulin heavy- or light-chain gene enhancers, leading to increased *C-MYC* expression and increased cell division.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Other large changes in chromosomal structure can result in the placement of two genes directly next to each other.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The result is the combination of two usually separate proteins into a new fusion protein.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This protein can have a new function that promotes cancer development.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Examples of this include the *ETV6*–*RUNX1* fusion gene that combines two factors that promote blood cell development and the *BCR*-*ABL1* fusion gene of the Philadelphia chromosome.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] *BCR*–*ABL1* encodes an always-activated tyrosine kinase that causes frequent cell division.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These mutations produce a cell that divides more often, even in the absence of growth factors.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Other genetic changes in B-cell ALL include changes in the number of chromosomes within the leukemic cells.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Gaining at least five additional chromosomes, called high hyperdiploidy, occurs more commonly.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Less often, chromosomes are lost, called hypodiploidy, which is associated with a poorer prognosis.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Additional common genetic changes in B-cell ALL involve non-inherited mutations to *PAX5* and *IKZF1*.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In T-cell ALL, *LYL1*, *TAL1*, *TLX1*, and *TLX3* rearrangements can occur.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Acute lymphoblastic leukemia results when enough of these genetic changes are present in a single lymphoblast.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In childhood ALL, for example, one fusion gene translocation is often found along with six to eight other ALL-related genetic changes.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The initial leukemic lymphoblast copies itself into an excessive number of new lymphoblasts, none of which can develop into functioning lymphocytes.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These lymphoblasts build up in the bone marrow and may spread to other sites in the body, such as lymph nodes, the mediastinum, the spleen, the testicles, and the brain, leading to the common symptoms of the disease.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Diagnosing ALL begins with a thorough medical history, physical examination, complete blood count, and blood smears.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] While many symptoms of ALL can be found in common illnesses, persistent or unexplained symptoms raise suspicion of cancer.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Because many features on the medical history and examination are not specific to ALL, further testing is often needed.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] A large number of white blood cells and lymphoblasts in the circulating blood can be suspicious for ALL because they indicate a rapid production of lymphoid cells in the marrow.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The higher these numbers, typically point to a worse prognosis.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] While white blood cell counts at initial presentation can vary significantly, circulating lymphoblast cells are seen on peripheral blood smears in the majority of cases.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] A bone marrow biopsy provides conclusive proof of ALL, typically with >20% of all cells being leukemic lymphoblasts.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] A lumbar puncture (also known as a spinal tap) can determine whether the spinal column and brain have been invaded.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Brain and spinal column involvement can be diagnosed either through confirmation of leukemic cells in the lumbar puncture or through clinical signs of CNS leukemia as described above.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Laboratory tests that might show abnormalities include blood count, kidney function, electrolyte, and liver enzyme tests.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Pathological examination, cytogenetics (in particular the presence of Philadelphia chromosome), and immunophenotyping establish whether the leukemic cells are myeloblastic (neutrophils, eosinophils, or basophils) or lymphoblastic (B lymphocytes or T lymphocytes).
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Cytogenetic testing on marrow samples can help classify the disease and predict its aggression.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Different mutations have been associated with shorter or longer survival.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Immunohistochemical testing may reveal TdT or CALLA antigens on the surface of leukemic cells.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] TdT is a protein expressed early in the development of pre-T and pre-B cells, whereas CALLA is an antigen found in 80% of ALL cases and also in the "blast crisis" of CML.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Medical imaging (such as ultrasound or CT scanning) can find invasion of other organs, commonly the lungs, liver, spleen, lymph nodes, brain, kidneys, and reproductive organs.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In addition to cell morphology and cytogenetics, immunophenotyping, a laboratory technique that identifies cell-surface proteins, is a key component in the diagnosis of ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The preferred method of immunophenotyping is through flow cytometry.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In malignant lymphoblasts of ALL, expression of terminal deoxynucleotidyl transferase (TdT) on the cell surface can help differentiate malignant lymphocyte cells from reactive lymphocytes, white blood cells that are reacting normally to an infection in the body.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] On the other hand, myeloperoxidase (MPO), a marker for the myeloid lineage, is typically not expressed.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Because precursor B cells and precursor T cells look the same, immunophenotyping can help differentiate the subtype of ALL and the maturity level of the malignant white blood cells.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The subtypes of ALL are determined by immunophenotype and maturation stages.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] An extensive panel of monoclonal antibodies to cell surface markers, particularly CD or cluster of differentiation markers, is used to classify cells by lineage.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Below are immunological markers associated with B-cell and T-cell ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Cytogenetic analysis has shown different proportions and frequencies of genetic abnormalities in cases of ALL from different age groups.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This information is particularly valuable for classification and can, in part, explain the different prognoses of these groups.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In regard to genetic analysis, cases can be stratified according to ploidy, the number of sets of chromosomes in the cell, and specific genetic abnormalities, such as translocations.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Hyperdiploid cells are defined as cells with more than 50 chromosomes, while hypodiploid cells are defined as cells with fewer than 44 chromosomes.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Hyperdiploid cases tend to carry a good prognosis, while hypodiploid cases do not.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] For example, the most common specific abnormality in childhood B-ALL is the t(12;21) *ETV6*–*RUNX1* translocation, in which the *RUNX1* gene, encoding a protein involved in transcriptional control of hemopoiesis, has been translocated and repressed by the *ETV6*–*RUNX1* fusion protein.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Below is a table with the frequencies of some cytogenetic translocations and molecular genetic abnormalities in ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Historically, before 2008, ALL was classified morphologically using the French-American-British (FAB) system that heavily relied on morphological assessment.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The FAB system takes into account information on size, cytoplasm, nucleoli, basophilia (color of cytoplasm), and vacuolation (bubble-like properties).
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] While some clinicians still use the FAB scheme to describe tumor cell appearance, much of this classification has been abandoned because of its limited impact on treatment choice and prognostic value.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In 2008, the World Health Organization (WHO) classification of ALL was developed to create a classification system that was more clinically relevant and could produce meaningful prognostic and treatment decisions.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This system recognized differences in genetic, immunophenotype, molecular, and morphological features through cytogenetic and molecular diagnostics tests.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This subtyping helps determine the prognosis and the most appropriate treatment for each specific case of ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Treatment aims to induce a lasting remission, defined as the absence of detectable cancer cells in the body (usually less than 5% blast cells in the bone marrow) or the absence of minimal residual disease.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Over the past several decades, there have been strides to increase the efficacy of treatment regimens, resulting in increased survival rates.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Possible treatments for acute leukemia include chemotherapy, steroids, radiation therapy, intensive combined treatments (including bone marrow or stem cell transplants), targeted therapy, and/or growth factors.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Chemotherapy is the initial treatment of choice, and most people with ALL receive a combination of medications.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] There are no surgical options because of the body-wide distribution of the malignant cells.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In general, cytotoxic chemotherapy for ALL combines multiple antileukemic drugs tailored to each person.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Chemotherapy for ALL consists of three phases: remission induction, intensification, and maintenance therapy.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Adult chemotherapy regimens mimic those of childhood ALL; however, they are linked with a higher risk of disease relapse with chemotherapy alone.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Two subtypes of ALL (B-cell ALL and T-cell ALL) require special considerations when it comes to selecting an appropriate treatment regimen in adults with ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] B-cell ALL is often associated with cytogenetic abnormalities (specifically, t(8;14), t (2;8), and t(8;22)), which require aggressive therapy consisting of brief, high-intensity regimens.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] T-cell ALL responds the most to cyclophosphamide-containing agents.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Recent updates on the treatment of adult acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL) include advancements in immunotherapy, particularly the use of monoclonal antibodies like blinatumomab and inotuzumab ozogamicin, which target specific cancer cells and are used alongside stem cell transplantation.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Additionally, tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs) such as imatinib and dasatinib are incorporated for Philadelphia chromosome-positive ALL, improving treatment outcomes.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Radiation therapy (or radiotherapy) is used on painful bony areas, in high disease burdens, or as part of the preparations for a bone marrow transplant (total body irradiation).
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In the past, physicians commonly utilized radiation in the form of whole-brain radiation for central nervous system prophylaxis, to prevent the occurrence and/or recurrence of leukemia in the brain.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Recent studies showed that CNS chemotherapy provided results as favorable, but with fewer developmental side effects.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] As a result, the use of whole-brain radiation has been more limited.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Most specialists in adult leukemia have abandoned the use of radiation therapy for CNS prophylaxis, instead using intrathecal chemotherapy.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Selection of biological targets based on their combinatorial effects on the leukemic lymphoblasts can lead to clinical trials for improvement in the effects of ALL treatment.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Tyrosine-kinase inhibitors (TKIs), such as imatinib, are often incorporated into the treatment plan for people with *Bcr-Abl1+ (Ph+)* ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] However, this subtype of ALL is frequently resistant to the combination of chemotherapy and TKIs, and allogeneic stem cell transplantation is often recommended upon relapse.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Blinatumomab is not only a promising add-on to chemotherapy in infant ALL, it is also a promising standalone therapy in children.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Chimeric antigen receptors (CARs) have been developed as a promising immunotherapy for ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This technology uses a single chain variable fragment (scFv) designed to recognize the cell-surface marker CD19 as a method of treating ALL.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] CD19 is a molecule on all B-cells and can be used to distinguish the potentially malignant B-cell population.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In this therapy, mice are immunized with the CD19 antigen and produce anti-CD19 antibodies.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Hybridomas developed from mouse spleen cells fused to a myeloma cell line can be developed as a source for the cDNA encoding the CD19-specific antibody.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The cDNA is sequenced and the sequence encoding the variable heavy and variable light chains of these antibodies are cloned together using a small peptide linker.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This resulting sequence encodes the scFv.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This can be cloned into a transgene, encoding the precursor to the CAR endodomain.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Varying arrangements of subunits serve as the endodomain.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] They generally consist of the hinge region that attaches to the scFv, a transmembrane region, the intracellular region of a costimulatory molecule such as CD28, and the intracellular domain of CD3-zeta containing ITAM repeats.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Other sequences frequently included are: 4-1bb and OX40.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The final transgene sequence, containing the scFv and endodomain sequences is then inserted into immune effector cells that are obtained from the person and expanded *in vitro*.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In trials these have been a type of T-cell capable of cytotoxicity.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Inserting the DNA into the effector cell can be accomplished by several methods.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Most commonly, this is done using a lentivirus that encodes the transgene.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Pseudotyped, self-inactivating lentiviruses are an effective method for the stable insertion of a desired transgene into the target cell.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Other methods include electroporation and transfection, but these are limited in their efficacy as transgene expression diminishes over time.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The gene-modified effector cells are then transplanted back into the person.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Typically, this process is done in conjunction with a conditioning regimen such as cyclophosphamide, which has been shown to potentiate the effects of infused T-cells.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] This effect has been attributed to making an immunologic space within which the cells populate.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The process as a whole results in an effector cell, typically a T-cell, that can recognize a tumor cell antigen in a manner that is independent of the major histocompatibility complex and which can initiate a cytotoxic response.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In 2017, tisagenlecleucel was approved by the FDA as a CAR-T therapy for people with acute B-cell lymphoblastic leukemia who did not respond adequately to other treatments or have relapsed.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In a 22-day process, the "drug" is customized for each person.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] T cells purified from each person are modified by a virus that inserts genes that encode a chimaeric antigen receptor into their DNA, one that recognizes leukemia cells.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Obecabtagene autoleucel (Aucatzyl) was approved for medical use in the United States in November 2024.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Typically, people who experience a relapse in their ALL after initial treatment have a poorer prognosis than those who remain in complete remission after induction therapy.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] It is unlikely that recurrent leukemia will respond favorably to the standard chemotherapy regimen that was initially implemented.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Instead, these people should be trialed on reinduction chemotherapy followed by allogeneic bone marrow transplantation.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These people in relapse may also receive blinatumomab, as it has been shown to increase remission rates and overall survival rates, without increased toxic effects.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Low-dose palliative radiation may also help reduce the burden of tumors inside or outside the central nervous system and alleviate some symptoms.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] There has also been evidence and approval of use for dasatinib, a tyrosine kinase inhibitor.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] It has shown efficacy in cases of people with Ph1-positive and imatinib-resistant ALL, but more research needs to be done on long-term survival and time to relapse.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Chemotherapies or stem cell transplantations may require a platelet transfusion to prevent bleeding.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Moreover, patients undergoing a stem cell transplantation can develop a graft-versus-host disease (GvHD).
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] It was evaluated whether mesenchymal stromal cells can be used to prevent GvHD.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The evidence is very uncertain about the therapeutic effect of mesenchymal stromal cells in treating graft-versus-host disease after stem cell transplantation on all-cause mortality and the complete disappearance of chronic acute graft-versus-host disease.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Mesenchymal stromal cells may result in little to no difference in the all-cause mortality, relapse of malignant disease, and incidence of acute and chronic graft-versus-host diseases if they are used for prophylactic reasons.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Adding physical exercises to the standard treatment for adult patients with haematological malignancies like ALL may result in little to no difference in mortality, quality of life, and physical functioning.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These exercises may result in a slight reduction in depression.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Furthermore, aerobic physical exercises probably reduce fatigue.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The evidence is very uncertain about the effect on anxiety and serious adverse events.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Brexucabtagene autoleucel (Tecartus) was approved by the FDA in October 2021 for the treatment of adults with relapsed or refractory B-cell precursor ALL, and later by the EMA in December 2021.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Each dose of brexucabtagene autoleucel is a customized treatment created using the recipient's immune system to help fight the leukemia.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The recipient's T cells, a type of white blood cell, are collected and genetically modified to include a new gene that facilitates the targeting and killing of the lymphoma cells.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] These modified T cells are then infused back into the recipient.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Before the development of chemotherapy regimens and hematopoietic stem cell transplants, children were surviving a median length of 3 months, largely due to either infection or bleeding.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Since the advent of chemotherapy, the prognosis for childhood leukemia has improved greatly, and children with ALL are estimated to have a 95% probability of achieving a successful remission after 4 weeks of initiating treatment.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] People in pediatric care with ALL in developed countries have a greater than 80% five-year survival rate.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] It is estimated that 60–80% of adults undergoing induction chemotherapy achieve complete remission after 4 weeks, and those over the age of 70 have a cure rate of 5%.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Cytogenetics, the study of characteristic large changes in the chromosomes of cancer cells, is an important predictor of outcome.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Some cytogenetic subtypes have a worse prognosis than others.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Unclassified ALL is considered to have an intermediate prognosis risk, somewhere in-between the good and poor risk categories.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Acute lymphoblastic leukemia affected about 876,000 people and resulted in 111,000 deaths globally in 2015.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] It occurs in both children and adults, with the highest rates seen between the ages of three and seven years.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Around 75% of cases occur before the age of 6, with a secondary rise after age 40.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] It is estimated to affect 1 in 1500 children.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Accounting for the broad age profiles of those affected, ALL newly occurs in about 1.7 per 100,000 people annually.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Acute lymphoblastic leukemia represents approximately 20% of adults and 80% of childhood leukemias, making it the most common childhood cancer.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Although 80 to 90% of children will have a long-term complete response with treatment, it remains the leading cause of cancer-related deaths among children.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] 85% of cases are of B-cell lineage and have an equal number of cases in both males and females.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The remaining 15% of the T-cell lineage has a male predominance.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Globally, ALL typically occurs more often in Caucasians, Hispanics, and Latin Americans than in Africans.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] In the US, ALL is more common in children from Caucasian (36 cases/million) and Hispanic (41 cases/million) descent when compared to those from African (15 cases/million) descent.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Leukemia is rarely associated with pregnancy, affecting only about 1 in 10,000 pregnant women.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] The management of leukemia in a pregnant woman depends primarily on the type of leukemia.
[src:cancer/acute-lymphoblastic-leukemia] Acute leukemias normally require prompt, aggressive treatment, despite significant risks of pregnancy loss and birth defects, especially if chemotherapy is given during the developmentally sensitive first trimester.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The **human immunodeficiency virus** (HIV) is a retrovirus that attacks the immune system.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Without treatment, it can lead to a spectrum of conditions including **acquired immunodeficiency syndrome** (AIDS).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It can be managed with treatment and become a manageable chronic health condition.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] While there is no cure or vaccine for HIV, antiretroviral treatment can slow the course of the disease, and, if used before significant disease progression, can extend the life expectancy of someone living with HIV to a nearly standard level.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] An HIV-positive person on treatment can expect to live a normal life, and die with the virus, not of it.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Effective treatment for HIV-positive people (people living with HIV) involves a life-long regimen of medicine to suppress the virus, making the viral load undetectable.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Early testing can show if treatment is needed to stop progression and to prevent infecting others.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Treatment is recommended as soon as the diagnosis is made.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] An HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Campaigns by UNAIDS and other organizations around the world have communicated this as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Without treatment the infection can interfere with the immune system, and eventually progress to AIDS, sometimes taking many years.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Following initial infection an individual may not notice any symptoms, or may experience a brief period of influenza-like illness.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] During this period the person may not know that they are HIV-positive, yet they will be able to pass on the virus.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Typically, this period is followed by a prolonged incubation period with no symptoms.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Eventually the HIV infection increases the risk of developing other infections such as tuberculosis, as well as other opportunistic infections, and tumors which are rare in people who have normal immune function.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The late stage is often also associated with unintended weight loss.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Without treatment, the life expectancy of an individual with HIV is around 11 years.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV is spread primarily by unprotected sex (including anal, oral and vaginal sex), contaminated hypodermic needles or blood transfusions, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Some bodily fluids, such as saliva, sweat, and tears, do not transmit the virus.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Oral sex has little risk of transmitting the virus.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Ways to avoid catching HIV and preventing the spread include safe sex, treatment to prevent infection ("PrEP"), treatment to stop infection in someone who has been recently exposed ("PEP"), treating those who are infected, and needle exchange programs.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Disease in a baby can often be prevented by giving both the mother and child antiretroviral medication.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Recognized worldwide in the early 1980s, HIV/AIDS has had a large impact on society, both as an illness and as a source of discrimination.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The disease also has large economic impacts.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There are many misconceptions about HIV/AIDS, such as the belief that it can be transmitted by casual non-sexual contact.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The disease has become subject to many controversies involving religion, including the Catholic Church's position not to support condom use as prevention.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It has attracted international medical and political attention as well as large-scale funding since it was identified in the 1980s.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV made the jump from other primates to humans in west-central Africa in the early-to-mid-20th century.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) in 1981 and its cause—HIV infection—was identified in the early part of the decade.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Between the first time AIDS was readily identified through 2024, the disease is estimated to have caused at least 42.3 million deaths worldwide.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In 2023, 630,000 people died from HIV-related causes, an estimated 1.3 million people acquired HIV and about 39.9 million people worldwide living with HIV, 65% of whom are in the World Health Organization (WHO) African Region.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a pandemic—a disease outbreak which is present over a large area and is actively spreading.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The United States' National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the Gates Foundation have pledged $200 million focused on developing a global cure for AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There are three main stages of HIV infection: acute infection, clinical latency, and AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The initial period following infection with HIV is called acute HIV, primary HIV or acute retroviral syndrome.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Many individuals develop an influenza-like illness, mononucleosis or glandular fever 2–4 weeks after exposure while others have no significant symptoms.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Symptoms occur in 40–90% of cases and most commonly include fever, large tender lymph nodes, throat inflammation, a rash, headache, tiredness, and/or sores of the mouth and genitals.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The rash, which occurs in 20–50% of cases, presents itself on the trunk and is maculopapular, classically.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Some people also develop opportunistic infections at this stage.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Gastrointestinal symptoms, such as vomiting or diarrhea may occur.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Neurological symptoms of peripheral neuropathy or Guillain–Barré syndrome also occur.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The duration of the symptoms varies, but is usually one or two weeks.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] These symptoms are not often recognized as signs of HIV infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Family doctors or hospitals can misdiagnose cases as one of the many common infectious diseases with similar symptoms.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Someone with an unexplained fever who may have been recently exposed to HIV should consider testing to find out if they have been infected.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The initial symptoms are followed by a stage called clinical latency, asymptomatic HIV, or chronic HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Without treatment, this second stage of the natural history of HIV infection can last from about three years to over 20 years (on average, about eight years).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] While typically there are few or no symptoms at first, near the end of this stage many people experience fever, weight loss, gastrointestinal problems and muscle pains.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Between 50% and 70% of people also develop persistent generalized lymphadenopathy, characterized by unexplained, non-painful enlargement of more than one group of lymph nodes (other than in the groin) for over three to six months.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Although most HIV-1 infected individuals have a detectable viral load and in the absence of treatment will eventually progress to AIDS, a small proportion (about 5%) retain high levels of CD4+ T cells (T helper cells) without antiretroviral therapy for more than five years.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] These individuals are classified as "HIV controllers" or long-term nonprogressors (LTNP).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Another group consists of those who maintain a low or undetectable viral load without anti-retroviral treatment, known as "elite controllers" or "elite suppressors".
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] They represent approximately 1 in 300 infected persons.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS) is defined as an HIV infection with either a CD4+ T cell count below 0.2 cells per mL or the occurrence of specific diseases associated with HIV infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In the absence of specific treatment, around half of people infected with HIV develop AIDS within ten years.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The most common initial conditions that alert to the presence of AIDS are pneumocystis pneumonia (40%), cachexia in the form of HIV wasting syndrome (20%), and esophageal candidiasis.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Other common signs include recurrent respiratory tract infections.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Opportunistic infections may be caused by bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites that are normally controlled by the immune system.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Which infections occur depends partly on what organisms are common in the person's environment.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] These infections may affect nearly every organ system.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] People with AIDS have an increased risk of developing various viral-induced cancers, including Kaposi's sarcoma, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Kaposi's sarcoma is the most common cancer, occurring in 10% to 20% of people with HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The second-most common cancer is lymphoma, which is the cause of death of nearly 16% of people with AIDS and is the initial sign of AIDS in 3% to 4%.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Both these cancers are associated with human herpesvirus 8 (HHV-8).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Cervical cancer occurs more frequently in those with AIDS because of its association with human papillomavirus (HPV).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Conjunctival cancer (of the layer that lines the inner part of eyelids and the white part of the eye) is also more common in those with HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Additionally, people with AIDS frequently have systemic symptoms such as prolonged fevers, sweats (particularly at night), swollen lymph nodes, chills, weakness, and unintended weight loss.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Diarrhea is another common symptom, present in about 90% of people with AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] They can also be affected by diverse psychiatric and neurological symptoms independent of opportunistic infections and cancers.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV is spread by three main routes: sexual contact, significant exposure to infected body fluids or tissues, and from mother to child during pregnancy, delivery, or breastfeeding (known as vertical transmission).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There is no risk of acquiring HIV if exposed to feces, nasal secretions, saliva, sputum, sweat, tears, urine, or vomit unless these are contaminated with blood.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It is also possible to be co-infected by more than one strain of HIV—a condition known as HIV superinfection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The most frequent mode of transmission of HIV is through sexual contact with an infected person.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] However, an HIV-positive person who has an undetectable viral load as a result of long-term treatment has effectively no risk of transmitting HIV sexually, known as Undetectable = Untransmittable.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The existence of functionally noncontagious HIV-positive people on antiretroviral therapy was controversially publicized in the 2008 Swiss Statement, and has since become accepted as medically sound.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Globally, the most common mode of HIV transmission is via sexual contacts between people of the opposite sex; however, the pattern of transmission varies among countries.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] As of 2017, most HIV transmission in the United States occurred among men who had sex with men (82% of new HIV diagnoses among males aged 13 and older and 70% of total new diagnoses).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In the US, gay and bisexual men aged 13 to 24 accounted for an estimated 92% of new HIV diagnoses among all men in their age group and 27% of new diagnoses among all gay and bisexual men.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] With regard to unprotected heterosexual contacts, estimates of the risk of HIV transmission per sexual act appear to be four to ten times higher in low-income countries than in high-income countries.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The risk of transmission from anal intercourse is especially high, estimated as 1.4–1.7% per act in both heterosexual and homosexual contacts.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] While the risk of transmission from oral sex is relatively low, it is still present.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The risk from receiving oral sex has been described as "nearly nil"; however, a few cases have been reported.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The per-act risk is estimated at 0–0.04% for receptive oral intercourse.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In settings involving prostitution in low-income countries, risk of female-to-male transmission has been estimated as 2.4% per act, and of male-to-female transmission as 0.05% per act.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Risk of transmission increases in the presence of many sexually transmitted infections and genital ulcers.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Genital ulcers increase the risk approximately fivefold.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Other sexually transmitted infections, such as gonorrhea, chlamydia, trichomoniasis, and bacterial vaginosis, are associated with somewhat smaller increases in risk of transmission.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The viral load of an infected person is an important risk factor in both sexual and mother-to-child transmission.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] During the first 2.5 months of an HIV infection, a person's infectiousness is twelve times higher due to the high viral load associated with acute HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] If the person is in the late stages of infection, rates of transmission are approximately eightfold greater.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Commercial sex workers (including those in pornography) have an increased likelihood of contracting HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Rough sex can be a factor associated with an increased risk of transmission.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Sexual assault is also believed to carry an increased risk of HIV transmission, as condoms are rarely worn, physical trauma to the vagina or rectum is likely, and there may be a greater risk of concurrent sexually transmitted infections.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The second-most frequent mode of HIV transmission is via blood and blood products.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Blood-borne transmission can be through needle-sharing during intravenous drug use, needle-stick injury, transfusion of contaminated blood or blood product, or medical injections with unsterilized equipment.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The risk from sharing a needle during drug injection is between 0.63% and 2.4% per act, with an average of 0.8%.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The risk of acquiring HIV from a needle stick from an HIV-infected person is estimated as 0.3% (about 1 in 333) per act and the risk following mucous membrane exposure to infected blood as 0.09% (about 1 in 1000) per act.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This risk may, however, be up to 5% if the introduced blood was from a person with a high viral load and the cut was deep.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In the United States, intravenous drug users made up 12% of all new cases of HIV in 2009, and in some areas more than 80% of people who inject drugs are predicted to be HIV-positive.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV is transmitted in about 90% of blood transfusions using infected blood.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In low-income countries, only half of transfusions may be appropriately screened (as of 2008), and it is estimated that up to 15% of HIV infections in these areas come from transfusion of infected blood and blood products, representing between 5% and 10% of global infections.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It is possible to acquire HIV from organ and tissue transplantation, although this is rare because of screening.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Unsafe medical injections play a role in HIV spread in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In 2007, between 12% and 17% of infections in this region were attributed to medical syringe use.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The World Health Organization estimates the risk of transmission as a result of a medical injection in Africa at 1.2%.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Risks are also associated with invasive procedures, assisted delivery, and dental care in this area of the world.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] People giving or receiving tattoos, piercings, and scarification are theoretically at risk of infection but no confirmed cases have been documented.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It is not possible for mosquitoes or other insects to transmit HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV can be transmitted from mother to child during pregnancy, during delivery, or through breast milk, resulting in the baby also contracting HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] As of 2008, vertical transmission accounted for about 90% of cases of HIV in children.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In the absence of treatment, the risk of transmission before or during birth is around 20%, and in those who also breastfeed 35%.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Treatment decreases this risk to less than 5%.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Antiretrovirals when taken by either the mother or the baby decrease the risk of transmission in those who do breastfeed.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] If blood contaminates food during pre-chewing it may pose a risk of transmission.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] If a woman is untreated, two years of breastfeeding results in an HIV/AIDS risk in her baby of about 17%.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Due to the increased risk of death without breastfeeding in many areas in the developing world, the World Health Organization recommends either exclusive breastfeeding or the provision of safe formula.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] All women known to be HIV-positive should be taking lifelong antiretroviral therapy.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV is the cause of the spectrum of disease known as HIV/AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV is a retrovirus that primarily infects components of the human immune system such as CD4+ T cells, macrophages and dendritic cells.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It directly and indirectly destroys CD4+ T cells.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV is a member of the genus *Lentivirus*, part of the family *Retroviridae*.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Lentiviruses share many morphological and biological characteristics.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Many species of mammals are infected by lentiviruses, which are characteristically responsible for long-duration illnesses with a long incubation period.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Lentiviruses are transmitted as single-stranded, positive-sense, enveloped RNA viruses.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Upon entry into the target cell, the viral RNA genome is converted (reverse transcribed) into double-stranded DNA by a virally encoded reverse transcriptase that is transported along with the viral genome in the virus particle.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The resulting viral DNA is then imported into the cell nucleus and integrated into the cellular DNA by a virally encoded integrase and host co-factors.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Once integrated, the virus may become latent, allowing the virus and its host cell to avoid detection by the immune system.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Alternatively, the virus may be transcribed, producing new RNA genomes and viral proteins that are packaged and released from the cell as new virus particles that begin the replication cycle anew.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV is now known to spread between CD4+ T cells by two parallel routes: cell-free spread and cell-to-cell spread, i.e. it employs hybrid spreading mechanisms.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In the cell-free spread, virus particles bud from an infected T cell, enter the blood/extracellular fluid and then infect another T cell following a chance encounter.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV can also disseminate by direct transmission from one cell to another by a process of cell-to-cell spread.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The hybrid spreading mechanisms of HIV contribute to the virus' ongoing replication against antiretroviral therapies.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Two types of HIV have been characterized: HIV-1 and HIV-2.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV-1 is the virus that was originally discovered (and initially referred to also as LAV or HTLV-III).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It is more virulent, more infective, and is the cause of the majority of HIV infections globally.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The lower infectivity of HIV-2 as compared with HIV-1 implies that fewer people exposed to HIV-2 will be infected per exposure.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Because of its relatively poor capacity for transmission, HIV-2 is largely confined to West Africa.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] After the virus enters the body, there is a period of rapid viral replication, leading to an abundance of virus in the peripheral blood.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] During primary infection, the level of HIV may reach several million virus particles per milliliter of blood.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This response is accompanied by a marked drop in the number of circulating CD4+ T cells.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The acute viremia is almost invariably associated with activation of CD8+ T cells, which kill HIV-infected cells, and subsequently with antibody production, or seroconversion.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The CD8+ T cell response is thought to be important in controlling virus levels, which peak and then decline, as the CD4+ T cell counts recover.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] A good CD8+ T cell response has been linked to slower disease progression and a better prognosis, though it does not eliminate the virus.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Ultimately, HIV causes AIDS by depleting CD4+ T cells.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This weakens the immune system and allows opportunistic infections.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] T cells are essential to the immune response and without them, the body cannot fight infections or kill cancerous cells.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The mechanism of CD4+ T cell depletion differs in the acute and chronic phases.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] During the acute phase, HIV-induced cell lysis and killing of infected cells by CD8+ T cells accounts for CD4+ T cell depletion, although apoptosis may also be a factor.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] During the chronic phase, the consequences of generalized immune activation coupled with the gradual loss of the ability of the immune system to generate new T cells appear to account for the slow decline in CD4+ T cell numbers.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Although the symptoms of immune deficiency characteristic of AIDS do not appear for years after a person is infected, the bulk of CD4+ T cell loss occurs during the first weeks of infection, especially in the intestinal mucosa, which harbors the majority of the lymphocytes found in the body.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The reason for the preferential loss of mucosal CD4+ T cells is that the majority of mucosal CD4+ T cells express the CCR5 protein which HIV uses as a co-receptor to gain access to the cells, whereas only a small fraction of CD4+ T cells in the bloodstream do so.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] A specific genetic change that alters the CCR5 protein when present in both chromosomes very effectively prevents HIV-1 infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV seeks out and destroys CCR5 expressing CD4+ T cells during acute infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] A vigorous immune response eventually controls the infection and initiates the clinically latent phase.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] CD4+ T cells in mucosal tissues remain particularly affected.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Continuous HIV replication causes a state of generalized immune activation persisting throughout the chronic phase.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Immune activation, which is reflected by the increased activation state of immune cells and release of pro-inflammatory cytokines, results from the activity of several HIV gene products and the immune response to ongoing HIV replication.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It is also linked to the breakdown of the immune surveillance system of the gastrointestinal mucosal barrier caused by the depletion of mucosal CD4+ T cells during the acute phase of disease.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV/AIDS related eye diseases are common among people living with this disease worldwide.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Among these diseases, HIV retinopathy is the most common condition.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This condition is seen in 40% to 60% of HIV positive patients.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It is also the most common cause of loss of vision in these patients.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV/AIDS is diagnosed via laboratory testing and then staged based on the presence of certain signs or symptoms.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV screening is recommended by the United States Preventive Services Task Force for all people 15 years to 65 years of age, including all pregnant women.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Additionally, testing is recommended for those at high risk, which includes anyone diagnosed with a sexually transmitted illness.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In many areas of the world, a third of HIV carriers only discover they are infected at an advanced stage of the disease when AIDS or severe immunodeficiency has become apparent.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Most people infected with HIV develop seroconverted (antigen-specific) antibodies within three to twelve weeks after the initial infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Diagnosis of primary HIV before seroconversion is done by measuring HIV-RNA or p24 antigen.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Positive results obtained by antibody or PCR testing are confirmed either by a different antibody or by PCR.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Antibody tests in children younger than 18 months are typically inaccurate, due to the continued presence of maternal antibodies.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Thus HIV infection can only be diagnosed by PCR testing for HIV RNA or DNA, or via testing for the p24 antigen.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Much of the world lacks access to reliable PCR testing, and people in many places simply wait until either symptoms develop or the child is old enough for accurate antibody testing.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In sub-Saharan Africa between 2007 and 2009, between 30% and 70% of the population were aware of their HIV status.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In 2009, between 3.6% and 42% of men and women in sub-Saharan countries were tested; this represented a significant increase compared to previous years.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Two main clinical staging systems are used to classify HIV and HIV-related disease for surveillance purposes: the WHO disease staging system for HIV infection and disease, and the CDC classification system for HIV infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The CDC's classification system is more frequently adopted in developed countries.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Since the WHO's staging system does not require laboratory tests, it is suited to the resource-restricted conditions encountered in developing countries, where it can also be used to help guide clinical management.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Despite their differences, the two systems allow a comparison for statistical purposes.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The World Health Organization first proposed a definition for AIDS in 1986.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Since then, the WHO classification has been updated and expanded several times, with the most recent version being published in 2007.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also created a classification system for HIV, and updated it in 2008 and 2014.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This system classifies HIV infections based on CD4 count and clinical symptoms, and describes the infection in five groups.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] For surveillance purposes, the AIDS diagnosis still stands even if, after treatment, the CD4+ T cell count rises to above 200 per μL of blood or other AIDS-defining illnesses are cured.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Consistent condom use reduces the risk of HIV transmission by approximately 80% over the long term.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] When condoms are used consistently by a couple in which one person is infected, the rate of HIV infection is less than 1% per year.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There is some evidence to suggest that female condoms may provide an equivalent level of protection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Application of a vaginal gel containing tenofovir (a reverse transcriptase inhibitor) immediately before sex seems to reduce infection rates by approximately 40% among African women.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] By contrast, use of the spermicide nonoxynol-9 may increase the risk of transmission due to its tendency to cause vaginal and rectal irritation.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Circumcision in sub-Saharan Africa "reduces the acquisition of HIV by heterosexual men by between 38% and 66% over 24 months".
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Owing to these studies, both the World Health Organization and UNAIDS recommended male circumcision in 2007 as a method of preventing female-to-male HIV transmission in areas with high rates of HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] However, whether it protects against male-to-female transmission is disputed, and whether it is of benefit in developed countries and among men who have sex with men is undetermined.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Programs encouraging sexual abstinence do not appear to affect subsequent HIV risk.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Evidence of any benefit from peer education is equally poor.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Comprehensive sexual education provided at school may decrease high-risk behavior.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] A substantial minority of young people continues to engage in high-risk practices despite knowing about HIV/AIDS, underestimating their own risk of becoming infected with HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Voluntary counseling and testing people for HIV does not affect risky behavior in those who test negative but does increase condom use in those who test positive.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Enhanced family planning services appear to increase the likelihood of women with HIV using contraception, compared to basic services.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It is not known whether treating other sexually transmitted infections is effective in preventing HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Antiretroviral treatment among people with HIV whose CD4 count ≤ 550 cells/μL is a very effective way to prevent HIV infection of their partner (a strategy known as treatment as prevention, or TASP).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] TASP is associated with a 10- to 20-fold reduction in transmission risk.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Pre-exposure prophylaxis for HIV ("PrEP") with a daily dose of the medications tenofovir, with or without emtricitabine, is effective in people at high risk including men who have sex with men, couples where one is HIV-positive, and young heterosexuals in Africa.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It may also be effective in intravenous drug users, with a study finding a decrease in risk of 0.7 to 0.4 per 100 person years.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The USPSTF, in 2019, recommended PrEP in those who are at high risk.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Universal precautions within the health care environment are believed to be effective in decreasing the risk of HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Intravenous drug use is an important risk factor, and harm reduction strategies such as needle-exchange programs and opioid substitution therapy appear effective in decreasing this risk.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] A course of antiretrovirals administered within 48 to 72 hours after exposure to HIV-positive blood or genital secretions is referred to as post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The use of the single agent zidovudine reduces the risk of an HIV infection five-fold following a needle-stick injury.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] As of 2013, the prevention regimen recommended in the United States consists of three medications—tenofovir, emtricitabine and raltegravir—as this may reduce the risk further.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] PEP treatment is recommended after a sexual assault when the perpetrator is known to be HIV-positive, but is controversial when their HIV status is unknown.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The duration of treatment is usually four weeks and is frequently associated with adverse effects—where zidovudine is used, about 70% of cases result in adverse effects such as nausea (24%), fatigue (22%), emotional distress (13%) and headaches (9%).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Programs to prevent the vertical transmission of HIV (from mothers to children) can reduce rates of transmission by 92–99%.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This primarily involves the use of a combination of antiviral medications during pregnancy and after birth in the infant, and potentially includes bottle feeding rather than breastfeeding.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] If replacement feeding is acceptable, feasible, affordable, sustainable and safe, mothers should avoid breastfeeding their infants; however, exclusive breastfeeding is recommended during the first months of life if this is not the case.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] If exclusive breastfeeding is carried out, the provision of extended antiretroviral prophylaxis to the infant decreases the risk of transmission.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In 2015, Cuba became the first country in the world to eradicate mother-to-child transmission of HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Currently there is no licensed vaccine for HIV or AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The most effective vaccine trial to date, RV 144, was published in 2009; it found a partial reduction in the risk of transmission of roughly 30%, stimulating some hope in the research community of developing a truly effective vaccine.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV/AIDS is a chronic condition, as there is currently no cure.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Treatment consists of highly active antiretroviral therapy (ART), which slows progression of the disease.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] As of 2022, 39 million people globally were living with HIV, and 29.8 million people were accessing ART.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Treatment also includes preventive and active treatment of opportunistic infections.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] As of July 2022, four people have been successfully cleared of HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Rapid initiation of antiretroviral therapy within one week of diagnosis appear to improve treatment outcomes in low and medium-income settings and is recommend for newly diagnosed HIV patients.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV retinopathy was a very common cause of blindness in people with AIDS before the introduction of highly active antiretroviral therapy, but its incidence is declining due to proper and timely management of AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Even if there are signs of retinopathy, it may reverse as CD4+ T cell counts increase.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Reversal of HIV retinopathy is a helpful sign of positive response to antiretroviral therapy in AIDS patients.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] But if HIV treatment is delayed it may lead to permanent visual loss.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Occurrence of HIV retinopathy may also be an indicator of therapeutic failure in AIDS patients undergoing treatment.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Current ART options are combinations (or "cocktails") consisting of at least three medications belonging to at least two types, or "classes", of antiretroviral agents.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There are also two drugs, ritonavir (RTV) and cobicistat (COBI) which can be used as pharmacokinetic (PK) enhancers (or boosters) to improve the PK profiles of PIs and the INSTI elvitegravir (EVG).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The World Health Organization and the United States recommend antiretrovirals in people of all ages (including pregnant women) as soon as the diagnosis is made, regardless of CD4 count.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Once treatment is begun, it is recommended that it is continued without breaks or "holidays".
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Many people are diagnosed only after treatment ideally should have begun.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The desired outcome of treatment is a long-term plasma HIV-RNA count below 50 copies/mL.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Levels to determine if treatment is effective are initially recommended after four weeks and once levels fall below 50 copies/mL checks every three to six months are typically adequate.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Inadequate control is deemed to be greater than 400 copies/mL.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Based on these criteria treatment is effective in more than 95% of people during the first year.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Benefits of treatment include a decreased risk of progression to AIDS and a decreased risk of death.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In the developing world, treatment also improves physical and mental health.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] With treatment, there is a 70% reduced risk of acquiring tuberculosis.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Additional benefits include a decreased risk of transmission of the disease to sexual partners and a decrease in mother-to-child transmission.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The effectiveness of treatment depends to a large part on compliance.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Reasons for non-adherence to treatment include poor access to medical care, inadequate social supports, mental illness and drug abuse.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The complexity of treatment regimens (due to pill numbers and dosing frequency) and adverse effects may reduce adherence.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Even though cost is an important issue with some medications, 47% of those who needed them were taking them in low- and middle-income countries as of 2010, and the rate of adherence is similar in low-income and high-income countries.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Specific adverse events are related to the antiretroviral agent taken.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Some relatively common adverse events include: lipodystrophy syndrome, dyslipidemia, and diabetes mellitus, especially with protease inhibitors.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Other common symptoms include diarrhea, and an increased risk of cardiovascular disease.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Newer recommended treatments are associated with fewer adverse effects.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Certain medications may be associated with birth defects and therefore may be unsuitable for women hoping to have children.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Treatment recommendations for children are somewhat different from those for adults.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The World Health Organization recommends treating all children less than five years of age; children above five are treated like adults.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The United States guidelines recommend treating all children less than 12 months of age and all those with HIV RNA counts greater than 100,000 copies/mL between one year and five years of age.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The European Medicines Agency (EMA) has recommended the granting of marketing authorizations for two new antiretroviral (ARV) medicines, rilpivirine (Rekambys) and cabotegravir (Vocabria), to be used together for the treatment of people with human immunodeficiency virus type 1 (HIV-1) infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The two medicines are the first ARVs that come in a long-acting injectable formulation.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This means that instead of daily pills, people receive intramuscular injections monthly or every two months.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Measures to prevent opportunistic infections are effective in many people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In addition to improving current disease, treatment with antiretrovirals reduces the risk of developing additional opportunistic infections.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Adults and adolescents who are living with HIV (even on anti-retroviral therapy) with no evidence of active tuberculosis in settings with high tuberculosis burden should receive isoniazid preventive therapy (IPT); the tuberculin skin test can be used to help decide if IPT is needed.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Children with HIV may benefit from screening for tuberculosis.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Vaccination against hepatitis A and B is advised for all people at risk of HIV before they become infected; however, it may also be given after infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole prophylaxis between four and six weeks of age, and ceasing breastfeeding of infants born to HIV-positive mothers, is recommended in resource-limited settings.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] It is also recommended to prevent PCP when a person's CD4 count is below 200 cells/uL and in those who have or have previously had PCP.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] People with substantial immunosuppression are also advised to receive prophylactic therapy for toxoplasmosis and MAC.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Appropriate preventive measures reduced the rate of these infections by 50% between 1992 and 1997.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Influenza vaccination and pneumococcal polysaccharide vaccine are often recommended in people with HIV/AIDS with some evidence of benefit.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) has issued recommendations regarding nutrient requirements in HIV/AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Dietary intake of micronutrients at RDA levels by HIV-infected adults is recommended by the WHO; higher intake of vitamin A, zinc, and iron can produce adverse effects in HIV-positive adults, and is not recommended unless there is documented deficiency.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Dietary supplementation for people who are infected with HIV and who have inadequate nutrition or dietary deficiencies may strengthen their immune systems or help them recover from infections; however, evidence indicating an overall benefit in morbidity or reduction in mortality is not consistent.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] People with HIV/AIDS are up to four times more likely to develop type 2 diabetes than those who are not tested positive with the virus.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Evidence for supplementation with selenium is mixed with some tentative evidence of benefit.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] For pregnant and lactating women with HIV, multivitamin supplement improves outcomes for both mothers and children.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] If the pregnant or lactating mother has been advised to take anti-retroviral medication to prevent mother-to-child HIV transmission, multivitamin supplements should not replace these treatments.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There is some evidence that vitamin A supplementation in children with an HIV infection reduces mortality and improves growth.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In the US, approximately 60% of people with HIV use various forms of complementary or alternative medicine, whose effectiveness has not been established.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There is not enough evidence to support the use of herbal medicines.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There is insufficient evidence to recommend or support the use of medical cannabis to try to increase appetite or weight gain.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV/AIDS has become a chronic rather than an acutely fatal disease in many areas of the world.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Prognosis varies between people, and both the CD4 count and viral load are useful for predicted outcomes.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Without treatment, average survival time after infection with HIV is estimated to be 9 to 11 years, depending on the HIV subtype.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] After the diagnosis of AIDS, if treatment is not available, survival ranges between 6 and 19 months.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] ART and appropriate prevention of opportunistic infections reduces the death rate by 80%, and raises the life expectancy for a newly diagnosed young adult to 20–50 years.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This is between two thirds and nearly that of the general population.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] If treatment is started late in the infection, prognosis is not as good: for example, if treatment is begun following the diagnosis of AIDS, life expectancy is ~10–40 years.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Half of infants born with HIV die before two years of age without treatment.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The primary causes of death from HIV/AIDS are opportunistic infections and cancer, both of which are frequently the result of the progressive failure of the immune system.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Risk of cancer appears to increase once the CD4 count is below 500/μL.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Tuberculosis co-infection is one of the leading causes of sickness and death in those with HIV/AIDS being present in a third of all HIV-infected people and causing 25% of HIV-related deaths.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV is also one of the most important risk factors for tuberculosis.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Hepatitis C is another very common co-infection where each disease increases the progression of the other.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The two most common cancers associated with HIV/AIDS are Kaposi's sarcoma and AIDS-related non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Other cancers that are more frequent include anal cancer, Burkitt's lymphoma, primary central nervous system lymphoma, and cervical cancer.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Even with anti-retroviral treatment, over the long term HIV-infected people may experience neurocognitive disorders, osteoporosis, neuropathy, cancers, nephropathy, and cardiovascular disease.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Some conditions, such as lipodystrophy, may be caused both by HIV and its treatment.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] HIV/AIDS is considered a global pandemic.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] As of 2022, approximately 39.0 million people worldwide are living with HIV, the number of new infections that year being about 1.3 million.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This is down from 2.1 million new infections in 2010.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Among new infections, 44% are in women and girls globally.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There were 630,000 AIDS related deaths in 2022, down from a peak of 2 million in 2005.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Among persons living with HIV (PLWH), the largest proportion reside in eastern and southern Africa (20.6 million, 54.6%).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] This region also had the highest rate of adult and child deaths due to AIDS in 2020 (310,000, 46.6%).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Sub-Saharan African adolescent girls and young women (aged 15–24 years) account for 77% of new infections among this age-range globally.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Here, in contrast to other regions, adolescent girls and young women are three times more likely to acquire HIV than age-matched males.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Despite these statistics, overall, new HIV infections and AIDS-related deaths have substantially decreased in this region since 2010.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Eastern Europe and central Asia has observed a 43% increase in new HIV infections and 32% increase in AIDS-related deaths since 2010, the highest of all global regions.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] These infections are predominantly distributed in persons who inject drugs, with gay men and other men who have sex with men or persons who engage in transaction sex the second and third populations most impacted in this region.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] At the end of 2019, United States indicated that approximately 1.2 million people aged ≥13 years were living with HIV, resulting in about 18,500 deaths in 2020.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] There were 34,800 estimated new infections in the US in 2019, 53% of which were in the southern region of the country.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In addition to geographic location, significant disparities in HIV incidence exist among men, Black or Hispanic populations, and men who reported male-to-male sexual contact.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimated that in that year, 158,500 people or 13% of infected Americans were unaware of their infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In the United Kingdom as of 2015, there were approximately 101,200 cases which resulted in 594 deaths.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] In Canada as of 2008, there were about 65,000 cases causing 53 deaths.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Between the first recognition of AIDS (in 1981) and 2009, it has led to nearly 30 million deaths.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Rates of HIV are lowest in North Africa and the Middle East (0.1% or less), East Asia (0.1%), and Western and Central Europe (0.2%).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] The worst-affected European countries, in 2009 and 2012 estimates, are Russia, Ukraine, Latvia, Moldova, Portugal and Belarus, in decreasing order of prevalence.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Groups at higher risk of acquiring HIV include persons who engage in transactional sex, gay men and other men who have sex with men, persons who inject drugs, transgender persons, and those who are incarcerated or detained.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p01] Climate change impacts HIV risk and the availability of and access to HIV prevention and treatment services, and can contribute to poor nutrition, impaired immunity, and poor adherence to treatment.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The first news story on the disease appeared on May 18, 1981, in the gay newspaper *New York Native*.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] AIDS was first clinically reported on June 5, 1981, with five cases in the United States.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The initial cases were a cluster of injecting drug users and gay men with no known cause of impaired immunity who showed symptoms of *Pneumocystis carinii* pneumonia (PCP), a rare opportunistic infection that was known to occur in people with very compromised immune systems.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Soon thereafter, a large number of homosexual men developed a generally rare skin cancer called Kaposi's sarcoma (KS).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Many more cases of PCP and KS emerged, alerting the U.S.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and a CDC task force was formed to monitor the outbreak.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In the early days, the CDC did not have an official name for the disease, often referring to it by way of diseases associated with it, such as lymphadenopathy, the disease after which the discoverers of HIV originally named the virus.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] They also used *Kaposi's sarcoma and opportunistic infections*, the name by which a task force had been set up in 1981.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] At one point the CDC referred to it as the "4H disease", as the syndrome seemed to affect heroin users, homosexuals, hemophiliacs, and Haitians.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The term *GRID*, which stood for gay-related immune deficiency, had also been coined.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] However, after determining that AIDS was not isolated to the gay community, it was realized that the term *GRID* was misleading, and the term *AIDS* was introduced at a meeting in July 1982.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] By September 1982 the CDC started referring to the disease as AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Historical reviews of the AIDS epidemic highlight that the earliest patients frequently presented with unusual skin-rashes, lymphadenopathy and weight loss—signs that alerted clinicians to a new infectious syndrome before HIV was identified.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Early clinical studies documented the disease's characteristic skin findings.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In 1985, British dermatologists Charles Farthing, Richard Staughton and Christopher Rowland Payne published the first detailed descriptions of cutaneous manifestations in people with AIDS and HTLV-III infection, including seborrhoeic dermatitis, folliculitis and vasculitic lesions.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In 1983, two separate research groups led by Robert Gallo and Luc Montagnier declared that a novel retrovirus may have been infecting people with AIDS, and published their findings in the same issue of the journal *Science*.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Gallo claimed a virus which his group had isolated from a person with AIDS was strikingly similar in shape to other human T-lymphotropic viruses (HTLVs) that his group had been the first to isolate.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Gallo's group called their newly isolated virus HTLV-III.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] At the same time, Montagnier's group isolated a virus from a person presenting with swelling of the lymph nodes of the neck and physical weakness, two characteristic symptoms of AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Contradicting the report from Gallo's group, Montagnier and his colleagues showed that core proteins of this virus were immunologically different from those of HTLV-I.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Montagnier's group named their isolated virus lymphadenopathy-associated virus (LAV).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] As these two viruses turned out to be the same, in 1986, LAV and HTLV-III were renamed HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The origin of HIV / AIDS and the circumstances that led to its emergence remain unsolved.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Both HIV-1 and HIV-2 are believed to have originated in non-human primates in West-central Africa and were transferred to humans in the early 20th century.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] HIV-1 appears to have originated in southern Cameroon through the evolution of SIV(cpz), a simian immunodeficiency virus (SIV) that infects wild chimpanzees (HIV-1 descends from the SIVcpz endemic in the chimpanzee subspecies *Pan troglodytes troglodytes*).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The closest relative of HIV-2 is SIV (smm), a virus of the sooty mangabey (*Cercocebus atys atys*), an Old World monkey living in coastal West Africa (from southern Senegal to western Ivory Coast).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] New World monkeys such as the owl monkey are resistant to HIV-1 infection, possibly because of a genomic fusion of two viral resistance genes.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] HIV-1 is thought to have jumped the species barrier on at least three separate occasions, giving rise to the three groups of the virus, M, N, and O.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] There is evidence that humans who participate in bushmeat activities, either as hunters or as bushmeat vendors, commonly acquire SIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] However, SIV is a weak virus which is typically suppressed by the human immune system within weeks of infection.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] It is thought that several transmissions of the virus from individual to individual in quick succession are necessary to allow it enough time to mutate into HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Furthermore, due to its relatively low person-to-person transmission rate, SIV can only spread throughout the population in the presence of one or more high-risk transmission channels, which are thought to have been absent in Africa before the 20th century.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Specific proposed high-risk transmission channels, allowing the virus to adapt to humans and spread throughout society, depend on the proposed timing of the animal-to-human crossing.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Genetic studies of the virus suggest that the most recent common ancestor of the HIV-1 M group dates back to c.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] While transmission rates of HIV during vaginal intercourse are low under regular circumstances, they are increased manyfold if one of the partners has a sexually transmitted infection causing genital ulcers.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] An alternative view holds that unsafe medical practices in Africa after World War II, such as unsterile reuse of single-use syringes during mass vaccination, antibiotic and anti-malaria treatment campaigns, were the initial vector that allowed the virus to adapt to humans and spread.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The earliest well-documented case of HIV in a human dates back to 1959 in the Congo.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The virus may have been present in the U.S. as early as the mid-to-late 1950s.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] A 16-year-old male named Robert Rayford presented with symptoms in 1966 and died in 1969.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In the 1970s, there were cases of people getting parasites and becoming sick with what was then called "gay bowel disease" but is now suspected to have been AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The earliest retrospectively described case of AIDS is believed to have been in Norway beginning in 1966, that of Arvid Noe.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In July 1960, in the wake of Congo's independence, the United Nations recruited Francophone experts and technicians from all over the world to assist in filling administrative gaps left by Belgium, who did not leave behind an African elite to run the country.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] By 1962, Haitians made up the second-largest group of well-educated experts (out of the 48 national groups recruited), that totaled around 4,500 in the country.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Jacques Pépin, a Canadian author of *The Origins of AIDS*, stipulates that Haiti was one of HIV's entry points to the U.S. and that a Haitian may have carried HIV back across the Atlantic in the 1960s.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The epidemic rapidly spread among high-risk groups (initially, sexually promiscuous men who have sex with men).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] By 1978, the prevalence of HIV-1 among gay male residents of New York City and San Francisco was estimated at 5%, suggesting that several thousand individuals in the country had been infected.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Stigma-related violence or the fear of violence prevents many people from seeking HIV testing, returning for their results, or securing treatment, possibly turning what could be a manageable chronic illness into a death sentence and perpetuating the spread of HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Often, AIDS stigma is expressed in conjunction with one or more other stigmas, particularly those associated with homosexuality, bisexuality, promiscuity, prostitution, and intravenous drug use.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In many developed countries, there is an association between AIDS and homosexuality or bisexuality, and this association is correlated with higher levels of sexual prejudice, such as anti-homosexual or anti-bisexual attitudes.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] There is also a perceived association between AIDS and all male-male sexual behavior, including sex between uninfected men.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] However, the dominant mode of spread worldwide for HIV remains heterosexual transmission.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The NAMES Project AIDS Memorial Quilt was conceived in 1985 to celebrate the lives of those who had died of AIDS when stigma prevented many from receiving funerals.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] It is now cared for by the National AIDS Memorial in San Francisco.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In 2003, as part of an overall reform of marriage and population legislation, it became legal for those diagnosed with AIDS to marry in China.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Between 2004 and 2020, Somen Debnath has travelled the world by bicycle promoting HIV / AIDS awareness.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] National Library of Medicine developed a traveling exhibition titled *Surviving and Thriving: AIDS, Politics, and Culture*; this covered medical research, the U.S. government's response, and personal stories from people with AIDS, caregivers, and activists.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Stigma has proved an obstacle to the update of PrEP.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Within the MSM community, the greatest barrier to PrEP use has been the stigma surrounding HIV and gay men.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Gay men on PrEP have experienced "slut-shaming".
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Numerous other barriers have been identified, including lack of quality LGBTQ care, cost, and adherence to medication use.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] HIV/AIDS affects the economics of both individuals and countries.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The gross domestic product of the most affected countries has decreased due to the lack of human capital.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Without proper nutrition, health care and medicine, large numbers of people die from AIDS-related complications.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Before death they will not only be unable to work, but will also require significant medical care.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] It is estimated that as of 2007 there were 12 million AIDS orphans.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Many are cared for by elderly grandparents.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Returning to work after beginning treatment for HIV/AIDS is difficult, and affected people often work less than the average worker.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Unemployment in people with HIV/AIDS also is associated with suicidal ideation, memory problems, and social isolation.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Employment increases self-esteem, sense of dignity, confidence, and quality of life for people with HIV/AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Anti-retroviral treatment may help people with HIV/AIDS work more, and may increase the chance that a person with HIV/AIDS will be employed (low-quality evidence).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] By affecting mainly young adults, AIDS reduces the taxable population, in turn reducing the resources available for public expenditures such as education and health services not related to AIDS, resulting in increasing pressure on the state's finances and slower growth of the economy.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] This causes a slower growth of the tax base, an effect that is reinforced if there are growing expenditures on treating the sick, training (to replace sick workers), sick pay, and caring for AIDS orphans.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] This is especially true if the sharp increase in adult mortality shifts the responsibility from the family to the government in caring for these orphans.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] At the household level, AIDS causes both loss of income and increased spending on healthcare.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] A study in Côte d'Ivoire showed that households having a person with HIV/AIDS spent twice as much on medical expenses as other households.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] This additional expenditure also leaves less income to spend on education and other personal or family investment.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The topic of religion and AIDS has become highly controversial, primarily because some religious authorities have publicly declared their opposition to the use of condoms.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Some religious organizations have claimed that prayer can cure HIV/AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In 2011, the BBC reported that some churches in London were claiming that prayer would cure AIDS, and the Hackney-based Centre for the Study of Sexual Health and HIV reported that several people stopped taking their medication, sometimes on the direct advice of their pastor, leading to many deaths.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] The Synagogue Church Of All Nations advertised an "anointing water" to promote God's healing, although the group denies advising people to stop taking medication.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] One of the first high-profile cases of AIDS was the American gay actor Rock Hudson.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] He had been diagnosed during 1984, announced that he had had the virus on July 25, 1985, and died a few months later on October 2, 1985.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Another notable British casualty of AIDS that year was Nicholas Eden, a gay politician and son of former prime minister Anthony Eden.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] On November 24, 1991, British rock star Freddie Mercury died from an AIDS-related illness, having revealed the diagnosis only on the previous day.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] One of the first high-profile heterosexual cases of the virus was American tennis player Arthur Ashe.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] He was diagnosed as HIV-positive on August 31, 1988, having contracted the virus from blood transfusions during heart surgery earlier in the 1980s.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Further tests within 24 hours of the initial diagnosis revealed that Ashe had AIDS, but he did not tell the public about his diagnosis until April 1992.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] He died as a result on February 6, 1993, aged 49.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Therese Frare's photograph of gay activist David Kirby, as he lay dying from AIDS while surrounded by family, was taken in April 1990.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] *Life* magazine said the photo became the one image "most powerfully identified with the HIV/AIDS epidemic." The photo was displayed in *Life*, was the winner of the World Press Photo, and acquired worldwide notoriety after being used in a United Colors of Benetton advertising campaign in 1992.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Many famous artists and AIDS activists such as Larry Kramer, Diamanda Galás and Rosa von Praunheim campaign for AIDS education and the rights of those affected.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] These artists worked with various media formats.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Criminal transmission of HIV is the intentional or reckless infection of a person with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Some countries or jurisdictions, including some areas of the United States, have laws that criminalize HIV transmission or exposure.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Others may charge the accused under laws enacted before the HIV pandemic.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In 1996, Ugandan-born Canadian Johnson Aziga was diagnosed with HIV; he subsequently had unprotected sex with eleven women without disclosing his diagnosis.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] By 2003, seven had contracted HIV; two died from complications related to AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Aziga was convicted of first-degree murder and sentenced to life imprisonment.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] There are many misconceptions about HIV and AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Three misconceptions are that AIDS can spread through casual contact, that sexual intercourse with a virgin will cure AIDS, and that HIV can infect only gay men and drug users.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] In 2014, some among the British public wrongly thought one could get HIV from kissing (16%), sharing a glass (5%), spitting (16%), a public toilet seat (4%), and coughing or sneezing (5%).
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Other misconceptions are that any act of anal intercourse between two uninfected gay men can lead to HIV infection, and that open discussion of HIV and homosexuality in schools will lead to increased rates of AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] A small group of individuals continue to dispute the connection between HIV and AIDS, the existence of HIV itself, or the validity of HIV testing and treatment methods.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] These claims, known as AIDS denialism, have been examined and rejected by the scientific community.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Several discredited conspiracy theories have held that HIV was created by scientists, either inadvertently or deliberately.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Operation INFEKTION was a worldwide Soviet active measures operation to spread the claim that the United States had created HIV/AIDS.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Surveys show that a significant number of people believed—and continue to believe—in such claims.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] HIV/AIDS research includes all medical research which attempts to prevent, treat, or cure HIV/AIDS, along with fundamental research about the nature of HIV as an infectious agent, and about AIDS as the disease caused by HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Many governments and research institutions participate in HIV/AIDS research.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] This research includes behavioral health interventions such as sex education, and drug development, such as research into microbicides for sexually transmitted diseases, HIV vaccines, and antiretroviral drugs.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Other medical research areas include the topics of pre-exposure prophylaxis, post-exposure prophylaxis, and circumcision and HIV.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Public health officials, researchers, and programs can gain a more comprehensive picture of the barriers they face, and the efficacy of current approaches to HIV treatment and prevention, by tracking standard HIV indicators.
[src:cancer/aids-hiv-p02] Use of common indicators is an increasing focus of development organizations and researchers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] About 33% of deaths from cancer are caused by tobacco and alcohol, obesity, lack of fruit and vegetables in the diet and lack of exercise.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Other factors include certain infections, exposure to ionizing radiation, and environmental pollutants.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Infection with specific viruses, bacteria, and parasites causes approximately 16–18% of cancers worldwide.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These infectious agents include *Helicobacter pylori*, hepatitis B, hepatitis C, and HPV.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) does not directly cause cancer, but it causes immune deficiency that can increase the risk of cancer from other infections, sometimes up to several thousandfold.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Vaccination against the hepatitis B virus and the human papillomavirus have been shown to nearly eliminate the risk of cancers caused by these viruses.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These environmental factors act, at least partly, by changing the genes of a cell.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Typically, many genetic changes are required before cancer develops.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Approximately 5–10% of cancers are due to inherited genetic defects.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancer can be detected by certain signs and symptoms or screening tests.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] It is then typically further investigated by medical imaging and confirmed by biopsy.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Early detection through screening is useful for cervical and colorectal cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The benefits of screening for breast cancer are controversial.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancer is often treated with some combination of radiation therapy, surgery, chemotherapy and targeted therapy.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] More personalized therapies that harness a patient's immune system are emerging in the field of cancer immunotherapy.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Palliative care is a medical specialty that delivers advanced pain and symptom management, which may be particularly important in those with advanced disease.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The chance of survival depends on the type of cancer and extent of disease at the start of treatment.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In children under 15 at diagnosis, the five-year survival rate in the developed world is on average 80%.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] For cancer in the United States, the average five-year survival rate is 66% for all ages.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In 2015, about 90.5 million people worldwide had cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In 2019, annual cancer cases grew by 23.6 million people, and there were 10 million deaths worldwide, representing over the previous decade increases of 26% and 21%, respectively.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The most common types of cancer in males are lung cancer, prostate cancer, colorectal cancer, and stomach cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In females, the most common types are breast cancer, colorectal cancer, lung cancer, and cervical cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] If skin cancer other than melanoma were included in total new cancer cases each year, it would account for around 40% of cases.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In children, acute lymphoblastic leukemia and brain tumors are most common, except in Africa, where non-Hodgkin lymphoma occurs more often.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In 2012, about 165,000 children under 15 years of age were diagnosed with cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The risk of cancer increases significantly with age, and many cancers occur more commonly in developed countries.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Rates are increasing as more people live to an old age and as lifestyle changes occur in the developing world.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The global total economic costs of cancer were estimated at US$1.16 trillion (equivalent to $1.71 trillion in 2025) per year as of 2010.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The word comes from the ancient Greek καρκίνος, meaning 'crab' and 'tumor'.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Greek physicians Hippocrates and Galen, among others, noted the similarity of crabs to some tumors with swollen veins.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The word was introduced in English in the modern medical sense around 1600.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancers comprise a large family of diseases that involve abnormal cell growth with the potential to invade or spread to other parts of the body.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] A neoplasm or tumor is a group of cells that have undergone unregulated growth and will often form a mass or lump, but may be distributed diffusely.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] All tumor cells show the six hallmarks of cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These characteristics are required to produce a malignant tumor.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The progression from normal cells to cells that can form a detectable mass to cancer involves multiple steps known as malignant progression.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] When cancer begins, it produces no symptoms.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Signs and symptoms appear as the mass grows or ulcerates.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The findings that result depend on cancer's type and location.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Many frequently occur in individuals who have other conditions.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancer can be difficult to diagnose and can be considered a "great imitator".
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] People may become anxious or depressed post-diagnosis.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The risk of suicide in people with cancer is approximately double.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Local symptoms may occur due to the mass of the tumor or its ulceration.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] For example, mass effects from lung cancer can block the bronchus resulting in cough or pneumonia; esophageal cancer can cause narrowing of the esophagus, making it difficult or painful to swallow; and colorectal cancer may lead to narrowing or blockages in the bowel, affecting bowel habits.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Masses in breasts or testicles may produce observable lumps.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Ulceration can cause bleeding that can lead to symptoms such as coughing up blood (lung cancer), anemia or rectal bleeding (colon cancer), blood in the urine (bladder cancer), or abnormal vaginal bleeding (endometrial or cervical cancer).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Although localized pain may occur in advanced cancer, the initial tumor is usually painless.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Some cancers can cause a buildup of fluid within the chest or abdomen.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Systemic symptoms may occur due to the body's response to the cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] This may include fatigue, unintentional weight loss, or skin changes.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Some cancers can cause a systemic inflammatory state that leads to ongoing muscle loss and weakness, known as cachexia.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Some cancers, such as Hodgkin's disease, leukemias, and liver or kidney cancers, can cause a persistent fever.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Shortness of breath, called dyspnea, is a common symptom of cancer and its treatment.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The causes of cancer-related dyspnea can include tumors in or around the lung, blocked airways, fluid in the lungs, pneumonia, or treatment reactions including an allergic response.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Treatment for dyspnea in patients with advanced cancer can include fans, bilevel ventilation, acupressure/reflexology and multicomponent nonpharmacological interventions.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Some systemic symptoms of cancer are caused by hormones or other molecules produced by the tumor, known as paraneoplastic syndromes.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Common paraneoplastic syndromes include hypercalcemia, which can cause altered mental state, constipation and dehydration, or hyponatremia, which can also cause altered mental status, vomiting, headaches, or seizures.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Metastasis is the spread of cancer to other locations in the body.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The dispersed tumors are called metastatic tumors, while the original is called the primary tumor.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Most cancer deaths are due to cancer that has metastasized.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Metastasis is common in the late stages of cancer and it can occur via the blood or the lymphatic system or both.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Different types of cancers tend to metastasize to particular organs.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Overall, the most common places for metastases to occur are the lungs, liver, brain, and the bones.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] While some cancers can be cured if detected early, metastatic cancer is more difficult to treat and control.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Nevertheless, some recent treatments are demonstrating encouraging results.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The majority of cancers, some 90–95% of cases, are due to environmental and lifestyle factors.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The remaining 5–10% are due to inherited genetics.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] *Environmental* refers to any cause that is not inherited, such as lifestyle, economic, and behavioral factors and not merely pollution.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Common environmental factors that contribute to cancer death include tobacco use (25–30%), diet and obesity (30–35%), infections (15–20%), radiation (both ionizing and non-ionizing, up to 10%), lack of physical activity, and pollution.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Psychological stress does not appear to be a risk factor for the onset of cancer, though it may worsen outcomes in those who already have cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Environmental or lifestyle factors that caused cancer to develop in an individual can be identified by analyzing mutational signatures from genomic sequencing of tumor DNA.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] For example, this can reveal if lung cancer was caused by tobacco smoke, if skin cancer was caused by UV radiation, or if secondary cancers were caused by previous chemotherapy treatment.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancer is generally not a transmissible disease.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Exceptions include rare transmissions that occur with pregnancies and occasional organ donors.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] However, transmissible infectious diseases such as hepatitis B, Epstein–Barr, HPV and HIV infections, can contribute to the development of cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Exposure to particular substances has been linked to specific types of cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These substances are called *carcinogens*.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Tobacco smoke, for example, causes 90% of lung cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Tobacco use can cause cancer throughout the body including in the mouth and throat, larynx, esophagus, stomach, bladder, kidney, cervix, colon/rectum, liver and pancreas.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Tobacco smoke contains over fifty known carcinogens, including nitrosamines and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Tobacco is responsible for about one in five cancer deaths worldwide and about one in three in the developed world.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Lung cancer death rates in the United States have mirrored smoking patterns, with increases in smoking followed by dramatic increases in lung cancer death rates and, more recently, decreases in smoking rates since the 1950s followed by decreases in lung cancer death rates in men since 1990.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Alcohol increases the risk of cancer of the breast (in women), throat, liver, osophagus, mouth, larynx, and colon.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In Western Europe, 10% of cancers in males and 3% of cancers in females are attributed to alcohol, especially liver and digestive tract cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancer from work-related substance exposures may cause between 2 and 20% of cases, causing at least 200,000 deaths.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancers such as lung cancer and mesothelioma can come from inhaling tobacco smoke or asbestos fibers, or leukemia from exposure to benzene.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Exposure to perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA), which is predominantly used in the production of Teflon, has been associated with an increased risk of kidney cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Chemotherapy drugs such as platinum-based compounds are carcinogens that increase the risk of secondary cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Azathioprine, an immunosuppressive medication, is a carcinogen that can cause primary tumors to develop.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Diet, physical inactivity, and obesity are related to up to 30–35% of cancer deaths.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In the United States, excess body weight is associated with the development of many types of cancer and is a factor in 14–20% of cancer deaths.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] A UK study including data on over 5 million people showed higher body mass index to be related to at least 10 types of cancer and responsible for around 12,000 cases each year in that country.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Physical inactivity is believed to contribute to cancer risk, not only through its effect on body weight but also through negative effects on the immune system and endocrine system.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] More than half of the effect from the diet is due to overnutrition (eating too much), rather than from eating too few vegetables or other healthful foods.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Some specific foods are linked to specific cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] A high-salt diet is linked to gastric cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Aflatoxin B1, a frequent food contaminant, causes liver cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Betel nut chewing can cause oral cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] National differences in dietary practices may partly explain differences in cancer incidence.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] For example, gastric cancer is more common in Japan due to its high-salt diet while colon cancer is more common in the United States.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Immigrant cancer profiles mirror those of their new country, often within one generation.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Worldwide, approximately 18% of cancer deaths are related to infectious diseases.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] This proportion ranges from a high of 25% in Africa to less than 10% in the developed world.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Viruses are the usual infectious agents that cause cancer but bacteria and parasites may also play a role.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Radiation exposure such as ultraviolet radiation and radioactive material is a risk factor for cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Many non-melanoma skin cancers are due to ultraviolet radiation, mostly from sunlight.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Sources of ionizing radiation include medical imaging and radon gas.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Residential exposure to radon gas has similar cancer risks as passive smoking.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Radiation is a more potent source of cancer when combined with other cancer-causing agents, such as radon plus tobacco smoke.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Radiation can cause cancer in most parts of the body, and at any age.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Children are twice as likely to develop radiation-induced leukemia as adults; radiation exposure before birth has ten times the effect.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Medical use of ionizing radiation is a small but growing source of radiation-induced cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Ionizing radiation may be used to treat other cancers, but this may, in some cases, induce a second form of cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] It is also used in some kinds of medical imaging.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Prolonged exposure to ultraviolet radiation from the sun can lead to melanoma and other skin malignancies.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Ultraviolet radiation, especially the non-ionizing medium wave UVB, is the cause of most non-melanoma skin cancers, which are the most common forms of cancer in the world.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Non-ionizing radio frequency radiation from mobile phones, electric power transmission and other similar sources has been described as a possible carcinogen by the World Health Organization's International Agency for Research on Cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Evidence, however, has not supported a concern.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] There is no demonstrable link between mobile phone radiation and cancer risk.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Most cancers are non-hereditary (sporadic).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Hereditary cancers are caused by inherited genetics.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Less than 0.3% of the population are carriers of a genetic mutation that has a large effect on cancer risk and these cause less than 3–10% of cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The relative risk of developing colorectal cancer (the cancer with the highest mortality) when a first-degree relative (parent, sibling or child) has been diagnosed with it is about 2.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The corresponding relative risk is 1.5 for lung cancer, and 1.9 for prostate cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] For breast cancer, the relative risk is 1.8 with a first-degree relative having developed it at 50 years of age or older, and 3.3 when the relative developed it when being younger than 50 years of age.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Taller people have an increased risk of cancer because they have more cells than shorter people.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Since height is genetically determined to a large extent, taller people have a heritable increase in cancer risk.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Some substances cause cancer primarily through their physical, rather than chemical, effects.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] A prominent example of this is prolonged exposure to asbestos, naturally occurring mineral fibers that are a major cause of mesothelioma (cancer of the serous membrane) usually the serous membrane surrounding the lungs.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Other substances in this category, including both naturally occurring and synthetic asbestos-like fibers, such as wollastonite, attapulgite, glass wool and rock wool, are believed to have similar effects.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Non-fibrous particulate materials that cause cancer include powdered metallic cobalt and nickel and crystalline silica (quartz, cristobalite and tridymite).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Usually, physical carcinogens must get inside the body (such as through inhalation) and require years of exposure to produce cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Physical trauma resulting in cancer is relatively rare.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Claims that breaking bones resulted in bone cancer, for example, have not been proven.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Similarly, physical trauma is not accepted as a cause for cervical cancer, breast cancer or brain cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] One accepted source is frequent, long-term application of hot objects to the body.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] It is possible that repeated burns on the same part of the body, such as those produced by kanger and kairo heaters (charcoal hand warmers), may produce skin cancer, especially if carcinogenic chemicals are also present.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Frequent consumption of scalding hot tea may produce esophageal cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Generally, it is believed that cancer arises, or a pre-existing cancer is encouraged, during the process of healing, rather than directly by the trauma.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] However, repeated injuries to the same tissues might promote excessive cell proliferation, which could then increase the odds of a cancerous mutation.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Chronic inflammation has been hypothesized to directly cause mutation.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Inflammation can contribute to proliferation, survival, angiogenesis and migration of cancer cells by influencing the tumor microenvironment.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Oncogenes build up an inflammatory pro-tumorigenic microenvironment.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Hormones also play a role in the development of cancer by promoting cell proliferation.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Insulin-like growth factors and their binding proteins play a key role in cancer cell proliferation, differentiation and apoptosis, suggesting possible involvement in carcinogenesis.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Hormones are important agents in sex-related cancers, such as cancer of the breast, endometrium, prostate, ovary and testis and also of thyroid cancer and bone cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] For example, the daughters of women who have breast cancer have significantly higher levels of estrogen and progesterone than the daughters of women without breast cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These higher hormone levels may explain their higher risk of breast cancer, even in the absence of a breast-cancer gene.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Similarly, men of African ancestry have significantly higher levels of testosterone than men of European ancestry and have a correspondingly higher level of prostate cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Men of Asian ancestry, with the lowest levels of testosterone-activating androstanediol glucuronide, have the lowest levels of prostate cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Other factors are relevant: obese people have higher levels of some hormones associated with cancer and a higher rate of those cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Women who take hormone replacement therapy have a higher risk of developing cancers associated with those hormones.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] On the other hand, people who exercise far more than average have lower levels of these hormones and lower risk of cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Osteosarcoma may be promoted by growth hormones.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Some treatments and prevention approaches leverage this cause by artificially reducing hormone levels and thus discouraging hormone-sensitive cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] There is an association between celiac disease and an increased risk of all cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] People with untreated celiac disease have a higher risk, but this risk decreases with time after diagnosis and strict treatment.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] This may be due to the adoption of a gluten-free diet, which seems to have a protective role against the development of malignancy in people with celiac disease.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] However, the delay in diagnosis and initiation of a gluten-free diet seems to increase the risk of malignancies.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Rates of gastrointestinal cancers are increased in people with Crohn's disease and ulcerative colitis, due to chronic inflammation.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Immunomodulators and biologic agents used to treat these diseases may promote the development of extra-intestinal malignancies.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancer is fundamentally a disease of tissue growth regulation.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] For a normal cell to transform into a cancer cell, the genes that regulate cell growth and differentiation must be altered.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The affected genes are divided into two broad categories.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Oncogenes are genes that promote cell growth and reproduction.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Tumor suppressor genes are genes that inhibit cell division and survival.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Malignant transformation can occur through the formation of novel oncogenes, the inappropriate over-expression of normal oncogenes, or by the under-expression or disabling of tumor suppressor genes.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Typically, changes in multiple genes are required to transform a normal cell into a cancer cell.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Genetic changes can occur at different levels and by different mechanisms.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The gain or loss of an entire chromosome can occur through errors in mitosis.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] More common are mutations, which are changes in the nucleotide sequence of genomic DNA.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Large-scale mutations involve the deletion or gain of a portion of a chromosome.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Genomic amplification occurs when a cell gains copies (often 20 or more) of a small chromosomal locus, usually containing one or more oncogenes and adjacent genetic material.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Translocation occurs when two separate chromosomal regions become abnormally fused, often at a characteristic location.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] A well-known example of this is the Philadelphia chromosome, or translocation of chromosomes 9 and 22, which occurs in chronic myelogenous leukemia and results in production of the BCR-Abl fusion protein, an oncogenic tyrosine kinase.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Small-scale mutations include point mutations, deletions, and insertions, which may occur in the promoter region of a gene and affect its expression, or may occur in the gene's coding sequence and alter the function or stability of its protein product.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Disruption of a single gene may also result from integration of genomic material from a DNA virus or retrovirus, leading to the expression of *viral* oncogenes in the affected cell and its descendants.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Replication of the data contained within the DNA of living cells will probabilistically result in some errors (mutations).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Complex error correction and prevention are built into the process and safeguard the cell against cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] If a significant error occurs, the damaged cell can self-destruct through programmed cell death, termed apoptosis.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] If the error control processes fail, then the mutations will survive and be passed along to daughter cells.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Some environments make errors more likely to arise and propagate.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Such environments can include the presence of disruptive substances called carcinogens, repeated physical injury, heat, ionising radiation, or hypoxia.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The transformation of a normal cell into cancer is akin to a chain reaction caused by initial errors, which compound into more severe errors, each progressively allowing the cell to escape more controls that limit normal tissue growth.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] This rebellion-like scenario is an undesirable survival of the fittest, where the driving forces of evolution work against the body's design and enforcement of order.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Once cancer has begun to develop, this ongoing process, termed *clonal evolution*, drives progression towards more invasive stages.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Clonal evolution leads to intra-tumour heterogeneity (cancer cells with heterogeneous mutations) that complicates the design of effective treatments, as therapies must account for the selective pressures they exert on the tumour cell population.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The classical view of cancer is a set of diseases driven by progressive genetic abnormalities that include mutations in tumor-suppressor genes and oncogenes, and in chromosomal abnormalities.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] A role for epigenetic alterations was identified in the early 21st century.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Epigenetic alterations are functionally relevant modifications to the genome that do not change the nucleotide sequence.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Examples of such modifications are changes in DNA methylation (hypermethylation and hypomethylation), histone modification and changes in chromosomal architecture (caused by inappropriate expression of proteins such as HMGA2 or HMGA1).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Each of these alterations regulates gene expression without altering the underlying DNA sequence.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These changes may remain through cell divisions, endure for multiple generations, and can be considered as equivalent to mutations.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Epigenetic alterations occur frequently in cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] As an example, one study listed protein coding genes that were frequently altered in their methylation in association with colon cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These included 147 hypermethylated and 27 hypomethylated genes.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Of the hypermethylated genes, 10 were hypermethylated in 100% of colon cancers and many others were hypermethylated in more than 50% of colon cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] While epigenetic alterations are found in cancers, the epigenetic alterations in DNA repair genes, causing reduced expression of DNA repair proteins, may be of particular importance.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Such alterations may occur early in the progression to cancer and are a possible cause of the genetic instability characteristic of cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Reduced expression of DNA repair genes disrupts DNA repair.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] This is shown in the figure at the 4th level from the top.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] (In the figure, red wording indicates the central role of DNA damage and defects in DNA repair in the progression to cancer.) When DNA repair is deficient DNA damage remains in cells at a higher than usual level (5th level) and causes increased frequencies of mutation and/or epimutation (6th level).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Mutation rates increase substantially in cells defective in DNA mismatch repair or in homologous recombinational repair (HRR).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Chromosomal rearrangements and aneuploidy (an abnormal number of chromosomes in a cell) also increase in HRR defective cells.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Higher levels of DNA damage cause increased mutation (right side of figure) and increased epimutation.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] During repair of DNA double strand breaks, or repair of other DNA damage, incompletely cleared repair sites can cause epigenetic gene silencing.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Deficient expression of DNA repair proteins due to an inherited mutation can increase cancer risks.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Individuals with an inherited impairment in any of 34 DNA repair genes (see article DNA repair-deficiency disorder) have increased cancer risk, with some defects ensuring a 100% lifetime chance of cancer (e.g. p53 mutations).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Germline DNA repair mutations are noted on the figure's left side.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] However, such germline mutations (which cause highly penetrant cancer syndromes) are the cause of only about 1 percent of cancers.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In sporadic cancers, deficiencies in DNA repair are occasionally caused by a mutation in a DNA repair gene but are much more frequently caused by epigenetic alterations that reduce or silence expression of DNA repair genes.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] This is indicated in the figure at the 3rd level.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Many studies of heavy metal-induced carcinogenesis show that such heavy metals cause a reduction in expression of DNA repair enzymes, some through epigenetic mechanisms.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] DNA repair inhibition is proposed to be a predominant mechanism in heavy metal-induced carcinogenicity.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] In addition, frequent epigenetic alterations of the DNA sequences code for small RNAs called microRNAs (or miRNAs). miRNAs do not code for proteins, but can "target" protein-coding genes and reduce their expression.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancers usually arise from an assemblage of mutations and epimutations that confer a selective advantage leading to clonal expansion (see Field defects in progression to cancer).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Mutations, however, may not be as frequent in cancers as epigenetic alterations.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] An average cancer of the breast or colon can have about 60 to 70 protein-altering mutations, of which about three or four may be "driver" mutations and the remaining ones may be "passenger" mutations.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The typical steps in metastasis are local invasion, intravasation (entry of cancer cells into a blood or lymph vessel), circulation through the body, extravasation (exit from the vessel into surrounding tissue), proliferation and angiogenesis (formation of new blood vessels to supply the tumour).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Different types of cancers tend to metastasize to particular organs, but overall the most common places for metastases to occur are the lungs, liver, brain and the bones.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Normal cells typically generate about 30% of energy from glycolysis, whereas most cancers rely on glycolysis for energy production (Warburg effect).
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] But a minority of cancer types rely on oxidative phosphorylation as the primary energy source, including lymphoma, leukemia, and endometrial cancer.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Even in these cases, however, the use of glycolysis as an energy source rarely exceeds 60%.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] A few cancers use glutamine as the major energy source, partly because it provides nitrogen required for nucleotide (DNA, RNA) synthesis.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cancer stem cells often use oxidative phosphorylation or glutamine as a primary energy source.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Most cancers are initially recognized either because of the appearance of signs or symptoms or through screening.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Neither of these leads to a definitive diagnosis, which requires the examination of a tissue sample by a pathologist.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] People with suspected cancer are investigated with medical tests.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These commonly include blood tests, X-rays, (contrast) CT scans and endoscopy.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] The tissue diagnosis from the biopsy indicates the type of cell that is proliferating, its histological grade, genetic abnormalities and other features.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Together, this information is useful to evaluate the prognosis and to choose the best treatment.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] Cytogenetics and immunohistochemistry are other types of tissue tests.
[src:cancer/cancer-p01] These tests provide information about molecular changes (such as mutations, fusion genes and numerical chromosome changes) and may thus also indicate the prognosis and best treatment.
